outlooksByWeek.1: The Chargers are again talking about a RB committee for 2021, but Ekeler should lead it and see tons of passing game work in the process. Washington's defense poses a tough matchup in Week 1, but this could ultimately lead to more dump-offs headed Ekeler's way. Ekeler projects as an RB1/RB2 this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Ekeler missed six games due to injury last season, but he was his usual productive self when healthy. During 10 active weeks, Ekeler racked up 933 yards and was fantasy's No. 8-scoring RB despite finding the end zone only three times. Even including the weeks he was sidelined, Ekeler finished fifth among backs in receptions and receiving yards for the second-consecutive season. Ekeler has still yet to clear 132 carries in a single season, but his heavy volume and elite efficiency as a receiver makes him one of the few backs in the league who could reasonably push for 90 receptions. The 26-year-old is a mid-to-back-end RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: With one of the bigger gaps between expected and actual rushing touchdowns last season, Elliott is due for a bounce-back campaign around the goal line. The first test of 2021 is admittedly challenging, with the Bucs allowing the fewest rushing yards and scores last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Elliott's 2020 season was considered a letdown by those who drafted him, which is really something when you consider that he finished top-five at RB in carries and targets while posting his fifth-consecutive top-12 fantasy campaign. The issue, of course, was a split season that saw Elliott post the third-most fantasy points during Dak Prescott's five starts (top-13 every week) before plummeting to 24th (one weekly finish better than 12th) the rest of the way. Prescott and Dallas' elite offensive line are back and healthy for 2021, which positions Elliott, who paced the NFL with 22 carries inside the 5-yard line last season, for a big rebound. The 26-year-old could prove to be a steal late in the first round of drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: Somewhat overlooked as the third member of the elite tight end tier in fantasy terms, Kittle is in a great spot to remind everyone how special he is in a matchup against a Detroit defense that allowed the third-most passing yards in the league last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Kittle - like so many of his 49ers teammates - will be eyeing a bounceback this season following an injury-plagued 2020. Kittle missed eight games and, even when active, his fantasy output was a bit erratic, as he put up point totals of 40 and 24, but managed only one other top-12 week. The good news is that he was still heavily-targeted (7.9 per game), his efficiency was great (top-5 at TE in YPT and RAC for the third straight season), and his overall fantasy production was good (top-three in fantasy PPG for the third consecutive season). Believe it or not, Kittle has never cleared five TDs in a single season, but the 27-year-old makes up for it with heavy volume and yardage totals. He remains a top-three fantasy TE.

outlooksByWeek.1: Even as his target share dipped last season, his claim of high-value red zone and endzone targets fueled another WR1 campaign. With the Bengals' porous pass defense up first, Thielen is in a nice spot to meet his projection.

player.seasonOutlook: He may have been overshadowed a bit by rookie Justin Jefferson, but Thielen put together another tremendous season in 2020. The 2014 UDFA posted a 74-925-14 receiving line, and his 20 end zone targets were three more than any other player. Thielen disappeared at times (six games with single-digit fantasy points) but delivered a high ceiling with six top-10 fantasy weeks (tied for third most) in 15 games. He has now finished three of the past four seasons as a top-10 fantasy WR. Thielen is now 31 years old, but Minnesota's lack of WR depth positions him to handle nearly one-quarter of the targets again this season. Consider Thielen a solid WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: After playing in only five games for the Detroit Lions last season, Golladay’s tenure with the Giants has begun ominously as he’s nursed a sore hamstring all preseason. Golladay is expected to make his Giants debut in Week 1 versus the Denver Broncos, but his lack of extensive work with Daniel Jones relegates Golladay to nothing more than flex consideration.

player.seasonOutlook: Golladay signed with the Giants after four seasons in Detroit. The 2017 third-round pick broke out with a WR21 fantasy campaign in 2018 before leaping up to WR9 on the back of a league-high 11 TDs in 2019. The wheels fell off in 2020, however, as injuries limited him to five games. The 6-foot-4 perimeter weapon will immediately step in as the Giants' top WR and figures to handle a target share in the same 22-23% range that he saw with the Lions. The Giants' QB play remains a question mark as Daniel Jones enters a make-or-break third season, but Golladay has a path to solid volume and figures to be very busy near the goal line. Consider him a fringe WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Steelers' resident slot maven, Smith-Schuster is looking to regain the elite efficiency that defined his first two pro seasons. Even if that doesn't happen, the USC product is a fine flex play facing a Bills secondary that could struggle against the slot.

player.seasonOutlook: Smith-Schuster is entering his fifth NFL season and has already posted three top-20 fantasy campaigns. Oh, and he's only 24 years old. Smith-Schuster peaked with a 111-1,426-7 receiving line and WR8 fantasy finish in 2018 before struggling with injuries and a Ben Roethlisberger-less offense in 2019. He bounced back to an extent last season, but it was a season only PPR's mother could love, as he caught 97 balls (seventh most) for 831 yards (36th). Smith-Schuster's 5.7 aDOT was second lowest among WRs, which led to a lowly 6.4 YPT (eighth lowest). He scored a career-high nine TDs, but his 5.8 OTD suggests he was way over his head. Smith-Schuster has a high PPR floor, but his targets could fall with Chase Claypool on the rise and Diontae Johnson in the mix. Consider him a WR3 and downgrade him in non-PPR.

outlooksByWeek.1: A hulking downfield threat, Claypool brings week-winning big-play ability to the field. Paired with a quarterback who has struggled to drive the ball after elbow surgery, it's arguable that Claypool's statistical floor is compromised for this meeting with the Bills outside cornerbacks.

player.seasonOutlook: The Steelers have a remarkable history when it comes to nailing their WR draft picks, so it comes as little surprise that Claypool was so impressive as a rookie. The 2020 second-round pick had his ups-and-downs but showed his ceiling with a 7-110-3 receiving line on 10 targets in Week 5. He went on to finish eighth among WRs with nine TDs (he scored two more in the team's playoff game) and 23rd at the position in fantasy points. Claypool saw at least six targets in 11 of 17 games, including 10 of his final 11. The 6-foot-4 vertical weapon will need to steal some targets away from JuJu Smith-Schuster and Diontae Johnson, but he's likely just getting started. The 23-year-old is on the WR3 radar with upside for more.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brady will be making his 300th career start when the Bucs kick off their campaign on Thursday night against the Cowboys. Dallas retooled their defense this offseason, but it's worth noting they ceded 19.3 fantasy points per game to passers last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Brady's first season with Tampa Bay resulted in a top-3 finish among QBs in pass attempts, passing yards and touchdowns, his best fantasy campaign since 2017 (eighth) and another Super Bowl MVP trophy. Is that good? It seems good. Brady's numbers benefit from Tampa Bay's pass-heavy scheme and he has an outstanding supporting cast led by Mike Evans, Chris Godwin, Antonio Brown and Rob Gronkowski, but note that minimal contributions with his legs barely allowed him to crack the top 10 in fantasy points in 2020. It's fair to wonder if he'll be able to sustain weekly QB1 numbers if his passing production slips even slightly, but the 44-year-old nonetheless remains a fringe starter.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jones had nine-plus TD catches in both of the last two seasons. He's also familiar with Jaguars OC Darrell Bevell's scheme from their time together in Detroit. Jones isn't necessarily going to be a weekly starter, but he's a viable WR3 against the Texans this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Jones signed with Jacksonville after spending his first four seasons with the Bengals and the last five with the Lions. Jones ranked third in routes and 18th in fantasy points as Detroit's No. 1 WR during most of 2020 but is likely to play a lesser role with D.J. Chark and Laviska Shenault Jr. in the fold in Jacksonville. Where Jones has shined is near the goal line, as he's scored nine-plus TDs in four seasons since 2013, including exactly nine in three of his past four campaigns. He's finished no lower than 20th in end zone targets and no lower than 25th in aDOT among WRs during that span. With rookie QB Trevor Lawrence likely to experience growing pains out of the gate, Jones is best valued as a borderline flex option in 12-team leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season confirmed that Pollard is among the most capable backup backs in the league. With Ezekiel Elliott entrenched as the lead back, Pollard is unlikely to accrue many touches on Thursday.

player.seasonOutlook: Pollard has impressed since being selected to serve Ezekiel Elliott's backup in the fourth round of the 2019 draft. After pacing the league in YAC (2.7) on 86 rookie-season carries, Pollard saw his numbers come back to earth this past season, but he still managed a serviceable 435 yards on 101 carries. Pollard has played more than 47% of Dallas' snaps only once - a 2020 Week 15 game in which Elliott was sidelined. Pollard was fantasy's top-scoring RB that week, producing 69 yards and 2 TDs on 12 carries and 63 yards on nine targets. Pollard lacks standalone value behind a healthy Elliott, but the high-volume Dallas offense is absolutely loaded in 2021, making the 24-year-old Pollard an elite insurance option.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Ravens D/ST checks in as one of the top options in Week 1 as they visit the Las Vegas Raiders in the season's first Monday Night Football affair. Last year, Baltimore's defense surrendered the second fewest points per game and the seventh lowest total yards per game.

player.seasonOutlook: Another year, another dominant performance by the Ravens' defense. Baltimore's unit posted its fifth straight top-five fantasy campaign in 2020. The Ravens' defense has ranked no worse than third in points allowed each of the past three seasons and has a massive 22 TDs during its past four campaigns. Baltimore led the NFL with 22 forced fumbles in 2020. It was a fairly quiet offseason for the unit, but 12 of the top 13 players in terms of 2020 defensive snaps remain on the roster. A loaded secondary led by Marlon Humphrey and Marcus Peters and a terrific interior defensive line led by Calais Campbell and Derek Wolfe helps anchor one of fantasy's top D/ST options in 2021.

outlooksByWeek.1: McKissic had 80 receptions for 589 yards in 2020, leading all NFL running backs in targets for the season. While most experts expect Antonio Gibson to ultimately eat into that target total, McKissic should still see plenty of looks early on. McKissic projects as a borderline flex play for Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Sometimes situation rules all and that was the case for McKissic in 2020. The journeyman scat back latched on with Washington as a complement to Antonio Gibson and went on to lead all running backs in routes (385) and targets (111), while finishing second in receptions (80) and receiving yards (589). McKissic played a much lesser role as a rusher (85-365-1), but his massive receiving role allowed him a 17th-place finish in fantasy points. It was his first finish better than 49th since he entered the league as a UDFA in 2016. McKissic's role figures to decline as Gibson's increases and new QB Ryan Fitzpatrick is sure to lean less on dumpoff throws than Alex Smith did, but the 27-year-old will remain involved in obvious passing situations. Consider him for your bench in deep PPR leagues, but the ceiling is low.

outlooksByWeek.1: Prior to suffering a season-ending knee injury last November, Burrow had the most completions and fifth-most pass yards through 10 career games in NFL history. With an unproven Cincinnati offensive line facing a potentially improved Minnesota defense, patience is likely best when it comes to Burrow as a starting fantasy option.

player.seasonOutlook: The phrase "volume is king" isn't often applied to quarterbacks, but it fits the bill when breaking down Burrow's rookie campaign. The 2020 first overall pick went down for the season in Week 11, but prior to that, he ranked first among QBs in snaps and drop backs, second in pass attempts, ninth in passing yards and 14th in fantasy points. Burrow's efficiency (65%, 6.7 YPA) was solid as far as rookie QBs go and he added value with his legs (37-142-2 rushing line). Burrow is an obvious candidate for a second-year leap and has a good core of targets in Ja'Marr Chase, Tee Higgins, Tyler Boyd and Joe Mixon. Consider him a good QB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Eagles aren't a very tough matchup for receivers, but Gage still need to prove he's worth trusting in fantasy lineups now that he's stepping into a bigger role for Atlanta.

player.seasonOutlook: Gage entered the 2020 season as an intriguing deep sleeper, and he quietly paid off for those who took a shot. Gage ranked 22nd at WR in targets and finished 37th in fantasy points despite finding the end zone only four times. Oddly, he was even better during five full games with Julio Jones and Calvin Ridley, handling a 20% target share and ranking 15th at WR in fantasy. With Jones now in Tennessee, Gage is now the favorite for No. 2 duties. On the other hand, Gage is a short-area target who adds little after the catch. His efficiency numbers have been very poor the past two seasons and Atlanta won't throw as often in new coach Arthur Smith's run-first, TE-friendly scheme. The 25-year-old's standing on the depth chart is enough to warrant a bench spot.

"Greg the Leg" has finished as a top-12 fantasy kicker each of the past four seasons, which includes the top spot in 2017 and a fifth-place finish in 2020, his first with Dallas. Zuerlein made "only" 82.9% of his FG attempts (34 of 41) last season, but that's a bit misleading, as six of the seven misses were on tries from 50-plus yards away (an area he's generally been good). The 41 attempts were also most in the NFL last season. Zuerlein's accuracy has been all over the map throughout his career, but he's set up nicely as the kicker in a loaded and high-volume offense in Dallas. The 33-year-old is a fine fantasy starter.

outlooksByWeek.1: Despite a strong camp and preseason, Jones was failed to unseat Latavius Murray as Alvin Kamara’s backup. However, it may not be long before Jones becomes the understudy. Even so, Jones is far from a fantasy factor.

All Diggs did in his debut season in Buffalo is establish several franchise records while leading the league in receptions and yards. As the lead target in one of the pass-happiest offenses in the league, Diggs is a top play this week even against a capable Steelers pass defense.

player.seasonOutlook: Diggs' first season in Buffalo was a giant success, as the 2015 fifth-round pick set new career-high and league-leading marks in targets (168), receptions (127) and receiving yards (1,535). Diggs' 29% target share was a new career-high, and his third-place finish in fantasy points marked his first season better than 10th. Diggs was solid in the first half of the season but exploded for four top-five weeks in his final seven games. Diggs also appeared in 16 regular season games for the first time in his six-year career. The 27-year-old is Josh Allen's top target in one of the league's highest-scoring and pass-heaviest offenses. Expect Diggs to deliver another strong WR1 campaign in 2021.

outlooksByWeek.1: Chubb is going to be exactly what you drafted him to be. With a solid projection for Cleveland's Week 1 game against the Chiefs, Chubb should be rolled out as a RB1 without exception.

player.seasonOutlook: Chubb enters his fourth NFL season as the lead dog in a Cleveland backfield that also includes standout Kareem Hunt. Chubb missed four games in 2020, but was very productive in 11 full regular season games with Hunt. He racked up 184 carries and 19 targets and only three RBs scored more fantasy points during the span. Aside of a rough Week 1, Chubb finished the other 10 games he played in full as a top-22 fantasy back. We know Chubb is a terrific rusher (his career 5.23 YPC and 2.28 YAC both rank second among qualified RBs), but we also saw an all-important boost in targets down the stretch last season (16 in his final four games). The 25-year-old will operate behind arguably the league's best offensive line and is a top-10 fantasy RB in all formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: Despite a notable dip in average depth of target, Hopkins still led all NFL receivers in first downs in 2020. Likely due some positive touchdown regression, Hopkins is a top option this week facing a subpar Tennessee secondary.

player.seasonOutlook: Hopkins didn't miss a beat in his first season in Arizona, posting his fourth consecutive top-five fantasy campaign and fifth since 2015. Hopkins finished second among WRs in targets, receptions and receiving yards. He saw at least seven targets in 15 of 16 games and has now handled a target share of at least 26% and air-yard share of at least 34% each of the past seven seasons. Despite the consistent usage, Hopkins was more boom/bust than usual, finishing as a top-10 fantasy WR in 50% of his appearances (second best), but outside the top 30 in 44% (15th best). Hopkins may be nearing the end of his prime, but the 29-year-old still figures to have another year or two of elite play in the tank. He's a solid WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: A thumb sprain has hindered Henderson a bit in practice as the Rams get ready for their opening home tilt with the Chicago Bears. The injury isn’t likely to affect Henderson’s production, but the acquisition of Sony Michel to help replace the loss of Cam Akers will. The backfield split is unclear, but with Henderson expected to receive more touches than Michel, Henderson is a low end RB2 in the opener.

player.seasonOutlook: Henderson is entering his third NFL season and, with Cam Akers out for the season, he'll be competing with newcomer Sony Michel for the Rams' lead back gig. It's a big opportunity for Henderson, as the 2019 third-round pick barely saw the field while behind Todd Gurley II as a rookie (184 yards on 43 touches) and then fell behind Akers last season. Akers missed most of Weeks 2-7 and also Week 16 last season. Henderson split backfield duties with Malcolm Brown during those seven games, racking up 96 carries and 16 targets on 210 snaps, compared to 54 carries and 18 targets on 227 snaps for Brown. Henderson was efficient and delivers a trio of top-11 fantasy weeks, but the low passing-game usage limited him to the 20th most fantasy points during the seven weeks (Brown was 42nd). Henderson can leap to the RB2 radar, but he'll first need to beat out Michel for lead back duties. The more-likely outcome is a two-headed committee that places both in the weekly flex discussion.

outlooksByWeek.1: Still among the league leaders in yards per route run last season, it's very possible that Jones still has at least one more special statistical season in him. The Cardinals were solid in coverage last season, but could face some issues on the outside against this size-and-speed unicorn.

player.seasonOutlook: Jones was traded to the Titans after spending his first 10 seasons with the Falcons. The trade comes after Jones' streak of six consecutive top-seven fantasy seasons came to an end in 2020. Injuries were, of course, the culprit, as Jones missed seven full games and the better part of two others (he missed a total of four the prior six seasons). The good news is that Jones was still dominant when healthy. In seven games he played in full, Jones posted a 45-700-3 receiving line and was fantasy's No. 3 WR. He posted a career-high 11.2 YPT, and he has now finished top-5 in YPRR in eight consecutive seasons. There are concerns, though, as Jones is 32 years old and likely to play second fiddle to A.J. Brown in Tennessee's run-first offense. Perhaps Jones has another elite season in the tank, but he's best valued as a mid-range WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season’s MVP opens defense of the award on the road against a talented New Orleans Saints defense. However, the game will be played outdoors in Jacksonville and not inside the Caesars Superdome. Rodgers remains a QB1 whenever he is under center.

player.seasonOutlook: Rodgers -- the reigning league MVP -- returns for his 17th season with the Packers. The 37-year-old's play (and fantasy production) had dropped off for a few seasons but got back on track in a big way in 2020. Rodgers completed a league-best 71% of his passes and paced the NFL with 48 passing TDs. Considering his age, declining rushing production and probable statistical regression to the mean -- he finished top-five in C%, YPA and TD% in 2020 after finishing no better than 15th each of the previous two seasons -- Rodgers is unlikely to repeat as the No. 2-scoring fantasy QB. Of course, he's finished as a top-10 QB in every season in which he's appeared in at least 15 games, so we can consider him a fairly safe QB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Despite a promising preseason, Singletary isn't yet a bankable fantasy option, as the Bills were still very pass-heavy with the first-team offense in the preseason and Zack Moss looms as real competition for work in this backfield. With the Steelers proving solid against the run last season, it's wise to let this backfield competition play out from your bench.

player.seasonOutlook: Following an impressive showing as a third-round rookie in 2019, Singletary appeared to be on the verge of a second-year breakout. Instead, Buffalo drafted Zack Moss, moved to a pass-heavy scheme and limited Singletary to a committee role. Despite ranking 10th among RBs in snaps last season, Singletary finished outside the Top 20 in touches and yards while scoring only two TDs. Incredibly, Singletary's best weekly fantasy finish was 15th and he was outside the top 30 in 10 of 16 games. In 14 games together, Singletary held the edge over Moss in snaps (482 to 397) and targets (43 to 24), but trailed in carries (119 to 117). Singletary is a solid player, but his role is unlikely to expand with Moss in the mix. The 24-year-old is a fine bench option with some deep league flex appeal.

outlooksByWeek.1: Players like Tonyan is why waiting on tight ends is a popular draft ploy. He’ll be hard-pressed to match last season’s 11 touchdowns, but the Packers’ coaching staff is reportedly excited about the overall improvements in his game. Start Tonyan with confidence as he profiles as a low end TE1 in the season opener with the New Orleans Saints.

player.seasonOutlook: Tonyan enjoyed a breakout season in 2020, posting a 52-586-11 receiving line on the way to finishing as fantasy's No. 4-scoring TE. He's 2021's "regression to the mean" Poster Boy, however, as his 59 targets tied for fewest by a top-12 fantasy TE over the past 12 seasons. Tonyan also paced TEs with an 88% catch rate and 18.6% TD rate, both of which aren't close to sustainable. Incredibly, Tonyan averaged 3.7 targets per game and failed to see more than six in a single game. With his rate stats bound to regress (some significantly), his volume will need to increase in 2021. The 27-year-old should be viewed as a TD-dependent, back-end TE1 who could easily fall back to TE2 territory.

outlooksByWeek.1: Hopes of Moss taking over lead duties in this backfield have dimmed lately; Moss has dealt with a hamstring ailment this summer, Devin Singletary had a strong camp, and Matt Breida presents some capable depth. Keeping tabs on Moss' role this week is wise, but it's tough to advocate actually starting anyone from this backfield against a solid Pittsburgh front.

player.seasonOutlook: The Bills selected Moss in the third round of the 2020 draft and immediately inserted him as a near-equal contributor to a backfield committee that also included Devin Singletary. Moss appeared in 13 regular season games and totaled 576 yards and five TDs on 125 touches. The limited role in Buffalo's pass-heavy scheme limited Moss to two weekly fantasy finishes better than 24th and one better than 15th. In 14 games together, Moss held the edge over Singletary in carries (119 to 117), but trailed in snaps (482 to 397) and targets (43 to 24). Moss was extremely effective during his time at Utah, but the 23-year-old remains stuck as, at best, the leader of a committee. Moss should be on benches in most formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Colts have placed Hilton (neck surgery) on injured reserve. The receiver cannot return until, at the earliest, Week 4. Stay tuned.

player.seasonOutlook: Hilton re-signed with the Colts, but will miss a few weeks to open the season due to injury. Once back, he'll be looking for a bounce-back campaign after finishing outside the top-40 fantasy WRs each of the past two seasons. Hilton's 2020 was a tale of two seasons, as he posted an ugly 29-327-0 line on 30 targets and was WR85 in fantasy through nine games before exploding for a 27-435-5 line on 42 targets (WR11 in fantasy) over his final six games. Hilton averaged 6.1 targets per game for the season (his lowest since his rookie season in 2012), and he has now missed at least one game each of the past three seasons (nine total). The 31-year-old will have another new QB (Carson Wentz) this season, and youngsters Michael Pittman Jr. and Parris Campbell are candidates for expanded roles. Hilton doesn't need to be drafted, but feel free to add him once he's healthy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Starting the season against Jacksonville in what's expected to be a three-man RB committee with Mark Ingram and David Johnson, Lindsay doesn't merit a spot in your Week 1 starting lineup. Keep that in mind, even though his role in Houston is worth monitoring as the season progresses.

player.seasonOutlook: Lindsay is now with the Texans after progressively falling out of favor during three seasons in Denver. The speedy and explosive Lindsay appeared to be a gem UDFA find by the Broncos back in 2018, having racked up 1,278 yards and 10 TDs on 227 touches as a rookie (he was RB13 in fantasy). However, a closer look showed an unsustainable pace in the TD and yardage departments and Lindsay's efficiency fell off in 2019 (still a solid RB19 fantasy campaign) before he was replaced by Melvin Gordon III atop the depth chart in 2020. The 27-year-old has struggled after contact throughout his career (1.4 YAC) and as a receiver (4.2 YPT), but is a fine change-of-pace option. He'll join the flex radar only if 29-year-old David Johnson misses time.

outlooksByWeek.1: The league's top pass rush from 2020 should have All-Pro edge menace T.J. Watt available for this opener against the Bills. It's never an ideal matchup to face a young MVP candidate quarterback like Josh Allen on the road, but at least the sack and turnover potential is present with this group.

player.seasonOutlook: Pittsburgh entered 2020 with the league's best defense and it showed up in fantasy. The Steelers' D/ST posted its second consecutive second-place finish after back-to-back top-eight campaigns the two seasons prior. Incredibly, the Steelers have now led the NFL in sacks in four straight seasons. They've also finished top-two in INTs and top-five in both yardage and points allowed each of the past two seasons. Most of the defensive core returns in 2021, with Steven Nelson, Mike Hilton and Bud Dupree the notable exceptions. Not much was done to replace the trio, but Devin Bush will be back from a torn ACL and the unit remains loaded with talent, including T.J. Watt, Minkah Fitzpatrick, Cameron Hayward, Stephon Tuitt and Joe Haden. Pittsburgh's D/ST should be one of the first units picked in your draft.

outlooksByWeek.1: Coming off of a strong 2020 season for the Raiders, Agholor opens his tenure in New England as a starter with big-play potential. However, a Week 1 matchup against a tough Miami secondary will not be the best opportunity for fantasy managers to see if their late-round investment in him pays off.

player.seasonOutlook: Agholor signed with the Patriots after enjoying a bit of a resurgence during his lone season with the Raiders. Following an up-and-down five years in Philadelphia, Agholor put together a strong 48-896-8 receiving line on 81 targets last season. He struggled with drops (seven) but was heavily targeted down field (15.4 aDOT was third highest among WRs) and answered the bell with plenty of explosive plays (his 18.7 YPR ranked second and his 11.1 YPT fourth). Agholor is entering his seventh NFL season at age 28 and has yet to post a top-20 fantasy campaign (he has finished better than 34th once: 2017). Agholor very well could lead New England in targets, but consistent flex production may be a lot to ask in a run-heavy scheme that will throw to its RBs and TEs often. Agholor is a fine bench option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Pascal had 44 receptions for 629 yards in 2020, and with T.Y. Hilton beginning the year on the IR, he should move up the Colts' WR depth chart to No. 3. That leaves him as being unlikely to have a huge role in Week 1, especially with several tight ends in the mix for targets. Don't feel obligated to wager on a big day from Pascal.

Bell was signed to the Ravens' practice squad early this week, but now may be pressed into action following the season-ending injury to Gus Edwards. The situation is fluid, but Bell could serve as a backup to Ty'Son Williams and is not a recommended lineup option in Week 1.

For the past two seasons, Murray has served as the more bruising change-of-pace back whenever Alvin Kamara needed a rest. Murray returns to that role, though he could eventually be usurped by Tony Jones Jr.. Murray is best suited as Alvin Kamara insurance, but even then it’s not 100% certain Murray is the right choice.

player.seasonOutlook: Murray is back in New Orleans as the early-down complement to the more-versatile Alvin Kamara. The role has allowed Murray 8.2 carries and 1.8 targets per game during outings in which both were active over the past two seasons. That's obviously not much and resulted in a grand total of three weekly finishes better than 25th (one better than 16th). Murray obviously lacks standalone value, though it's worth noting he put up 307 yards and four TDs on 62 touches during two games Kamara missed with an injury in 2019. Murray is now 31 years old and his stock is down with Drew Brees retired and Tony Jones Jr. now in the mix for carries. Murray is a decent insurance policy, but no more.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Cardinals are somewhat thin at cornerback. The Titans are not thin at wideout. Brown is looking to open with a strong showing as Tennessee's incumbent big-play threat.

player.seasonOutlook: Following what was a low-volume but high-efficiency rookie campaign in 2019, Brown took a big leap forward with a larger piece of the pie in 2020. The 2019 second-round pick missed Weeks 2-3 with an injury, but during the other 15 weeks of the season, he was the fourth-highest-scoring WR in fantasy. Brown averaged a hefty 28% target share (37% air-yard share) during 15 active weeks (which included one playoff game). Brown has finished top-three in YPRR and top-eight in YPT, RAC and TD% during both of his NFL seasons, and it's unlikely that we've seen the 24-year-old's best NFL season. Julio Jones is now in the mix, but Corey Davis and Jonnu Smith are gone, so Brown still has a path to a huge target share. Consider him a solid fantasy WR1 with a high ceiling.

outlooksByWeek.1: Four running backs topped 300 touches last season and all four ended up in the top eight in fantasy production at the position. Shocking study, we know, but the key being just how much volume drives fantasy success from the backfield. With a heavy preseason workload indicating a Le'Veon-like workload for Harris, this first matchup with an undersized Bills front could prove rewarding.

player.seasonOutlook: Harris was scooped up by Pittsburgh with the 24th pick of April's draft. Standout RB prospects from Alabama are nothing new, but Harris is a bit of a unicorn in that he's huge (6-foot-2, 230 pounds) and an outstanding receiver with a large catch radius (43-425-4 receiving line in 2020). Absurdly elusive for his size, Harris' 3.1 forced missed tackle rate is third best in this year's class during the past three seasons. Harris is severely lacking speed, but his combination of size, strength, tackle breaking, elusiveness and receiving ability supplies him with a high ceiling. He'll immediately slot in as the undisputed lead back. Pittsburgh's offensive line isn't as good as in year's past, but volume is king and Harris could push for 20 touches as soon as Week 1. He's immediately a fringe RB1 with elite upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: An historic rookie campaign included Jefferson establishing the all-time rookie receiving record despite not seeing starting snaps until Week 3. The Bengals struggled to contain the pass last season, setting up Jefferson as a strong play.

player.seasonOutlook: Jefferson was targeted three times in each of his first two NFL games last season -- and then the training wheels were removed. The 2020 first-round pick handled a massive 28% target share (8.6 per game) from that point forward, which included a ridiculous 43% air-yard share. The LSU product hit double-digit targets in five of his final six games and only three wide receivers scored more fantasy points after Week 2. Jefferson's efficiency matched his top-end usage, as his 11.0 YPT and 2.8 YPRR both ranked second at the position. The 22-year-old won't be short on targets in Minnesota's run-first but high-scoring scheme and makes for a solid WR1 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Sixth in receiving yardage among running backs last season, it will be interesting to see how Edmonds is used on early downs. James Conner looms as a threat for rushing work, but it helps Edmonds' case that the Titans allowed nearly five catches per game to backfields last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Edmonds has thus far been limited to change-of-pace/passing-down duties, having yet to clear 97 carries in a single season. His career 4.8 YPC is strong, but is inflated by a league-high rate of runs against light boxes over the past two seasons. Edmonds ranked no lower than seventh at RB in receptions, receiving yards and TD catches last season, which helped him to a career-best 25th-place finish in fantasy points. He's played more than two-thirds of Arizona's snaps in only two career games, but came up big in both with a 29-touch, 150-yard, 3-TD effort in 2019 and a 28-touch, 88-yard showing in 2020. With Drake out and James Conner in as the team's lead rusher, Edmonds figures to see only a slight or perhaps moderate increase in workload. He's a flex option in PPR.

outlooksByWeek.1: Not only is this dude a generational prospect by both athletic and production measures, he's joining an offensive system that has consistently leaned on production from this position. The key question is just how many routes and targets will Pitts see against an exploitable Eagles back seven?

player.seasonOutlook: Pitts was selected by Atlanta with the fourth-overall pick of April's draft. The Florida product is one of the best TE prospects in league history, as he sports an elite combination of height (6-foot-6), athleticism and ball skills to go along with terrific speed (4.44 40 yard dash) and hands (no drops in 2020). Oh, and he's only 20 years old. Pitts is on the thin side (245 pounds) and a work in progress as a blocker, but that won't hinder his elite upside as a pass catcher. He'll immediately step in as Matt Ryan's No. 2 target behind Calvin Ridley. Yes, rookie TEs are rarely fantasy relevant, but if anyone can be the exception, it's Pitts. Consider him a mid-range TE1.

outlooksByWeek.1: After finishing 2019 as the top fantasy quarterback, Jackson slipped last season but was still a top-10 signal caller. However, his skills improved a tad and with upgraded receivers and a healthy offensive line, Jackson should again be one of the best at the position. Week 1 offers a great chance for Jackson to reestablish himself, facing one of the weakest defenses in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: The NFL's premier rushing QB, Jackson has paced the position in carries and rushing yards during all three of his NFL seasons. That includes a 159-1005-7 rushing line in 2020 that was actually a step back from what he produced during his MVP run in 2019. Jackson also accounted for 370 fewer passing yards, 10 fewer TDs and three more INTs, while regressing from first to 10th in fantasy points. The return to earth was expected after the historic and unsustainable 2019 showing. The 24-year-old is expected to throw the ball more in 2021after the team added Rashod Bateman, Tylan Wallace and Sammy Watkins to a group that also includes Marquise Brown and Mark Andrews . Jackson should be valued as a mid-range QB1 with upside for more.

outlooksByWeek.1: Somewhat lost in the shuffle of offseason hype for the 49ers' young offense, Samuel is looking to build off his brilliant 2019 rookie season. With most of his work possibly coming around the line of scrimmage, Samuel makes for an interesting flex in deeper PPR leagues given this sweet matchup with Detroit.

player.seasonOutlook: Samuel is entering his third NFL season after suffering through an injury-plagued 2020. Samuel managed five full games, averaging a hefty 25% target share (8.2 per game) while also handling 4% of the team's carries. His 30-356-1 receiving line was good enough for the 17th-most fantasy points among WRs. As a second-round rookie in 2019, Samuel put up 697 yards and four TDs from Week 10-17 and was WR9 in fantasy during that stretch. He kept it up in the playoffs with 229 yards on 16 touches. Samuel is primarily used near the line of scrimmage (7.7 aDOT in 2019, 2.4 in 2020) and is a terror with the ball in his hands (career 9.5 RAC). A weapon as both a receiver and rusher, Samuel shouldn't struggle for touches in Kyle Shanahan's offense. He's a good flex target.

outlooksByWeek.1: With a solid role in a productive Cleveland offense, barring unforeseen developments, Landry should be viewed as a viable WR3 candidate on a weekly basis. He's certainly in that range for this week's game against the Chiefs.

player.seasonOutlook: The Browns made a big leap forward as a franchise in 2020, but it came at the expense of Landry's usage and fantasy production. The 2014 second-round pick had handled at least 8.1 targets per game in five consecutive seasons and, despite Odell Beckham Jr. missing 10 games, Landry's targets fell to 6.7 per game in 2020. His WR33 fantasy finish was the worst of his seven-year career and came after five consecutive top-18 campaigns. Even more concerning, Landry had 32 targets in six full games with Beckham (5.3 per game) and was WR40 in fantasy (which would've been worse if not for a passing TD). The 28-year-old is a short-range target who doesn't score much in a run-first scheme. Especially with Beckham back, Landry is likely to cap out as a flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brought into Detroit to bolster what the team hopes is a productive rushing attack, Williams should be pretty busy in his debut with the Lions. The 49ers allowed the sixth-fewest fantasy points to backfields last season, curbing Williams' appeal this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Williams signed with the Lions after spending his first four NFL seasons with the Packers. The 2017 fourth-round pick spent most of his Green Bay tenure in a situational role, maxing out at a 48% snap share in 2018 while averaging 125.0 carries and 38.3 targets per season. Williams is expected to play a similar role in Detroit, operating as a change-of-pace option behind D'Andre Swift. Williams' efficiency has generally been pedestrian at best and he's yet to finish a season better than 32nd in fantasy points. Williams won't have consistent standalone value when Swift is healthy, but, if Swift were to miss time, the 26-year-old would lead the backfield and could push for RB2 production.

Smith is expected to miss the 2021 season. He had been set to enter his third NFL season and was finally positioned for a breakout following the offseason departure of Kyle Rudolph. Smith has thus far been limited to 91 targets in 29 regular season games (3.1 per game) and has yet to deliver a top-20 fantasy season. With Rudolph sidelined during the final four weeks of 2020, Smith posted a strong 15-183-3 receiving line and was TE4 in fantasy, though he was out-targeted 22-to-20 by Tyler Conklin. The 2019 second-round pick turned 23 in August, so he'll again be a breakout candidate in 2022.

outlooksByWeek.1: With nine targets and three rushing attempts in the preseason, Moore could eventually emerge as a dynamic contributor for this offense. With Moore likely fourth or fifth in line for targets to open the season, he's not yet a viable fantasy option.

player.seasonOutlook: Moore was selected by Arizona with the 49th overall pick of April's draft. The Purdue product is a 5-foot-7, 180-pound short-area, slot receiver. He led the nation with 114 receptions as a true freshman in 2018 before combining to play eight games due to injury and a COVID-related opt out over the past two seasons. Moore aligned in the slot 88% of the time during his time at Purdue, and his 5.2 aDOT and 11.0 YPR are lowest in this year's rookie class during that span. Expect the speedy Moore (reported 4.28 40) to find his way to a slot/rusher/returner role in the pros, though short-term playing time may be limited with DeAndre Hopkins, A.J. Green and Christian Kirk also on the depth chart. Moore is a shaky bet for immediate flex production, but his pedigree in a good offense makes him worth a late flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: One of the top defensive options this week, the 49ers finally have a healthy secondary and face a Detroit offense without much firepower in the passing phase.

player.seasonOutlook: The 49ers D/ST entered the 2020 season fresh off a third-place finish the season prior and with one of the league's best defenses on paper. Unfortunately, injuries struck early and often and the unit fell to a 13th-place finish. Despite the step back, the 49ers still managed eight top-10 fantasy weeks, which was seventh most. They finished top five in yardage allowed for the second year in a row, but fell to 21st in forced turnovers (20) and 22nd in sacks (30). Expect a bounce back in 2021 with a healthy Nick Bosa (and perhaps Dee Ford) set to rejoin the likes of Arik Armstead, Fred Warner, Jason Verrett, Jimmie Ward and 2020 first-round pick Javon Kinlaw. Losing defensive coordinator Robert Saleh hurts, but the talent is here for the 49ers' D/ST to return to top-10 status in fantasy.

Tucker has played eight seasons in the NFL and has finished 11th or better at the position in all eight. However, as good as he's been, he's never finished a season in the top spot. His eighth-place finish in 2020 was his worst finish since 2015. Volume was the primary culprit, as he matched a career low with 29 FG attempts (set in 2019), but his conversion rate of 89.7% was also his lowest since 2015. On the plus side, he made 52 of 53 extra points. Baltimore hasn't been as reliant on Tucker with Lamar Jackson under center (as opposed to the Joe Flacco era), but the 31-year-old is still the best in the business. He remains a strong fantasy option.

outlooksByWeek.1: After a decade with the Bengals, Green debuts for the Cardinals this week in a matchup against a Titans defense that struggled against the pass last season. Given Green's lack of production last season, it's wise to consider him a depth piece to open the season.

player.seasonOutlook: Green signed with Arizona after spending his first 10 NFL seasons in Cincinnati. Green is coming off what was easily the worst season of his career, ranking 27th in routes and 26th in targets among WRs, but outside the top 60 in receptions, yardage and TDs. His 44% catch rate, 4.9 YPT and 1.8 RAC all ranked dead last, though 25% of balls thrown his way were off target (seventh highest). Perhaps Green will bounce back opposite heavily targeted DeAndre Hopkins, but it's hard to get too excited, considering he's now 33 years old, last season's performance and his shaky durability (missed at least six games in three of the past five seasons). Despite the concerns, Green's resume and starting gig in a good offense are enough to make him worth a late flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: Stevenson demonstrated playmaking ability in extensive preseason action this summer, but it was mostly against third-teamers. With Damien Harris and James White both having better-defined roles ahead of him, Stevenson shouldn't be on your starting radar Week 1 against Miami.

player.seasonOutlook: The Patriots selected Stevenson in the fourth round of April's draft. If you're a fan of elusiveness, tackle breaking and post-contact production, Stevenson is your guy. The Oklahoma product is oversized at 6-foot, 229 pounds, but is still quick and shifty. Granted his sample size is very small (165 carries, 34 targets over 19 career games), but Stevenson's 4.8 YAC and 2.9 forced missed tackle rate during the span are both tops in this year's class. As if that wasn't enough, Stevenson averaged 12.8 receiving yards after the catch (RAC) on his 28 career receptions, which is fourth-best in this class. On the other hand, Stevenson is one of the oldest backs in this class (23) and doesn't have a clear path to short-term touches with Damien Harris, J.J. Taylor and James White in the mix. Stevenson is worth drafting in dynasty only.

outlooksByWeek.1: With Mark Ingram II leaving for the Houston Texans, Williams was slated to compete with Justice Hill for the No. 3 spot in the Ravens. However, following season-ending injuries to J.K. Dobbins, Gus Edwards and Hill, Williams is now the top option on Monday night, and is a legit flex play.

A fourth-round pick in this year's draft, Hubbard has ample playmaking ability. That said, he opens the season as the top insurance policy for Christian McCaffrey in Carolina. Barring an unforeseen injury to McCaffrey, a limited role will keep Hubbard from being a viable fantasy play against the Jets in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Carolina drafted Hubbard in the fourth round of April's draft. Hubbard has been busy the past three seasons at Oklahoma State, racking up 585 carries and 67 targets on 1,514 snaps. He stands 6-foot-1, 207 pounds and showed serviceable ability as both as rusher and receiver while also chipping in as a kick returner, though his elusiveness doesn't stack up with this year's top RB prospects. Hubbard has struggled with fumbles (11 in his career) and his efficiency plummeted in seven 2020 games after a terrific breakout campaign in 2019 that saw him produce 2,292 yards and 21 touchdowns in 13 games. Hubbard is the favorite to slide in as a Mike Davis replacement behind Christian McCaffrey. The rookie is an interesting deep-league insurance option.

outlooksByWeek.1: If you ignore the weeks where he attempted to play through a high-ankle sprain, McLaurin has been one of the most efficient wideouts in football. Now, he gets a legitimate NFL quarterback (Ryan Fitzpatrick) throwing him the ball. Week 1 provides a neutral defensive matchup, helping put McLaurin in the WR1/WR2 conversation.

player.seasonOutlook: McLaurin has handled 25% of Washington's targets and a massive 41% of the air yards since he was drafted in the third round of the 2019 draft. The Ohio State product flashed with a 58-919-7 receiving line in 14 games as a rookie before leaping to an 87-1,118-4 line in 15 games last season. McLaurin's per-target numbers took a hit last season, as the presence of conservative Alex Smith and Kyle Allen led to an aDOT drop from 13.8 in 2019 to 9.6 in 2020. New QB Ryan Fitzpatrick (top 10 in aDOT each season from 2015-19) should allow the speedy McLaurin more vertical targets and likely more scoring opportunities (six end zone targets last season ranked 64th). The 25-year-old is primed for his best NFL season and very much on the WR1 radar.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jones has the skill set to be a three-down back and with Jamaal Williams joining the Detroit Lions, Jones snap count could increase. However, with AJ Dillon as the new backup, Jones could lose short yardage and some goal line opportunities. However, that won’t stop him from earning RB1 status which is where he checks in for Week 1’s tilt with the New Orleans Saints.

player.seasonOutlook: Jones re-signed with Green Bay during the offseason and returns as the high-scoring Packers' feature back. The 26-year-old has been a top-five fantasy back each of the past two seasons, ranking no lower than 15th in carries and no lower than 12th in targets among RBs during both campaigns. The hyper-efficient Jones has finished three of four seasons with a YPC above 5.4 and his career-best 2.4 YAC ranked second in 2020. Durability is a slight issue (he's missed at least two games in three of his four NFL seasons), but not enough to knock him more than slightly on draft day. With Jamaal Williams out and AJ Dillon as the team's No. 2 back, Jones may lose some goal line work, but perhaps gain snaps and receiving work. Jones is locked in as a solid RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: While Woods and new quarterback Matthew Stafford did not play together in the preseason, they worked diligently during practice to develop a rapport. Woods will again play alongside Cooper Kupp, with Woods being the better downfield option. Last season, the Rams had trouble throwing deep, but with Stafford that should change, rendering Woods with WR2 status.

player.seasonOutlook: Woods remains one of the most underappreciated players in fantasy. The 2013 second-round pick debuted with the Rams in 2017 and was WR15 in fantasy during 12 healthy games. He's appeared in 15-plus games each of the past three seasons and finished all three as a top-14 fantasy WR. Woods' usage has been incredibly consistent (target shares of 24%, 25%, 23% and 24% during the four Rams seasons), and he has finished no lower than third in snaps, 11th in routes, 13th in targets and 11th in receptions at the position during any of the past three campaigns. Woods was over his head in the TD department in 2020 (8 TDs, 4.9 OTD) but also adds value as a rusher (60 carries over the past three seasons). The 29-year-old is a low-ceiling but solid WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Lockett actually had more targets and more receptions (a nice, round 100) than fellow Seattle standout WR DK Metcalf in 2020. A faster-paced offense in 2021 should only add to his ceiling. As such, Lockett firmly projects as a WR2 this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Lockett finished 2020 as fantasy's No. 8-scoring WR, but his season was extremely boom/bust. Of his 265 fantasy points, 123 (46%) came in three games, as did eight of his 10 TDs. Lockett scored 51 more fantasy points than any other WR those weeks, but he was WR32 with nine finishes of 40th or worse the other 13 weeks. Despite the inconsistent production, Lockett averaged a career-high 8.3 targets per game (25% share) and has finished as a top-16 fantasy WR each of the past three seasons. He's also finished no lower than sixth in catch rate, TDs and end zone targets each of the past two seasons. Seattle may lean more on the run in 2021, but Lockett and DK Metcalf are the team's clear top two weapons and assured generous target shares. The 28-year-old is a fringe WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Fourth among NFL backs in catches last year and now angling for a featured role in Atlanta's offense, we could learn a lot about Davis' role with the Falcons in this initial matchup against the Eagles. Philadelphia allowed the 10th-most rushing yards last season, aiding his case as a flex option.

player.seasonOutlook: Davis signed with the Falcons during the offseason. The 28-year-old's NFL ride has been interesting, as the 2015 fourth-round pick battled to hang on to a roster spot in San Francisco, Seattle and Chicago before joining Carolina as Christian McCaffrey's primary back up during the 2019 season. McCaffrey's injury-plagued 2020 vaulted Davis into the fantasy spotlight and he ended up 13th among RBs in touches and yardage while finishing 12th in fantasy points. Davis' efficiency was unimpressive (3.9 YPC, 5.3 YPT) and his role was reduced down the stretch, but a sizable workload in the pass game (his 70 targets ranked fifth) led to the fantasy success. Atlanta didn't draft a back, so Davis is expected to be the lead runner in 2021. He could sneak into the RB2 mix, but is best-viewed as a low-ceiling flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: Is there a fantasy WR3 with more upside potential than Beckham? Given his level of talent and anticipated role as the deep threat in Cleveland's offense, Beckham is a lower-end fantasy starter more than capable of delivering WR1 totals in any given week -- including against the Chiefs in the opener.

player.seasonOutlook: Beckham returns for his third season with the Browns following an underwhelming 2019 (74-1,035-4 receiving line and one top-10 fantasy week) and injury-plagued 2020 (23-319-3 line and one weekly finish better than 19th in six tries). That's decent production for most players but not for a player who averaged a 96-1,374-12 line during his first three seasons in the league (2014-16). Durability remains a major concern, as Beckham is averaging 9.8 games played over the past four seasons. Beckham turns 29 this year, and his target ceiling is capped a bit in Cleveland's run-first (albeit efficient) offense. Beckham should be valued as a WR3 but has the talent to leap back into the WR2 mix.

outlooksByWeek.1: Trey Sermon looms as a real threat to take over this backfield, but that might be more of a 2022 narrative if Mostert stays healthy. After all, he's averaged 5.6 yards per carry since joining the 49ers in 2016 and should be in line for double-digit carries against a suspect Detroit defense to open the season.

player.seasonOutlook: Mostert is eyeing a bounceback 2021 campaign after injuries limited him to 120 touches in eight games last season. Mostert was fantasy's No. 16 RB during those eight outings and, granted he's only handled 282 career carries, but his 5.6 YPC is tops in the NFL since he entered the league in 2015. Mostert's usage has been fairly consistent. He handled 51% of the carries and 8% of the targets during the final eight games of 2019 and was at 51% and 8%, respectively, during the six games he played in full in 2020. The 29-year-old doesn't see much receiving work (career 48 targets), has durability concerns (has appeared in more than 11 regular season games once) and will face competition from third-round rookie Trey Sermon. Mostert will be on the RB2/flex radar early on, but expect Sermon's role to progressively increase.

outlooksByWeek.1: On a Bengals offense that could combine pace and passing volume this season, Boyd's role from the slot could prove quite rewarding. The Vikings were shoddy in coverage last season, setting up Boyd with a nice initial outlook.

player.seasonOutlook: Seemingly a certified bust after his first two NFL seasons, Boyd has emerged as one of the league's best and most-reliable slot WRs. The 2016 second-round pick peaked with a pair of top-20 fantasy campaigns in 2018-19 and was well on his way to a similar showing in the first half of 2020. Boyd was WR9 in fantasy during Joe Burrow's 10 starts, but Burrow went down with a torn ACL in Week 11 and injuries limited Boyd to three more full games the rest of the season. Boyd joins Tee Higgins and Ja'Marr Chase to form one of the league's best WR trios and all three will be busy in Cincinnati's WR-friendly scheme. Boyd doesn't find the end zone much (one season with more than five TDs), but the 26-year-old is a good bet for his fourth consecutive season averaging a target share above 20%. He's a fine WR3.

outlooksByWeek.1: Some draft analysts deemed Sermon the best back in the 2020 class. There's a real chance Sermon becomes a fantasy force as a rookie, but it's best to let him prove so in this fist matchup with the Lions.

player.seasonOutlook: Sermon was selected by the 49ers in the third round of April's draft. The Ohio State standout is a big (6-foot, 215 pounds) and explosive runner who racked up 455 carries during three seasons at Oklahoma and one at OSU. Sermon sports a good elusiveness profile (top-10 in this class in both YAC and Forced Missed Tackle rate over the past three seasons), but lacks speed and his potential passing-game contributions are a question mark (he totaled 48 receptions and caught a weak 79% of his targets from 2018-20). Sermon has a shot to eventually emerge as the 49ers' lead back, but he'll first need to overtake Raheem Mostert. Sermon lacks standalone value in the short term, but he's a strong target for a bench stash considering Mostert's durability woes.

outlooksByWeek.1: Expected to be the receiving component in a backfield committee likely to include Phillip Lindsay and Mark Ingram, Johnson's anticipated role makes him only a low-end flex play against the Jaguars this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Johnson was better than it seemed last season, delivering a top-10 fantasy showing in 33% of his games (ninth-best) and falling outside the top-30 only once in 11 full games. He played 81% of Houston's snaps, averaging 13.2 carries and 4.1 targets per game, which allowed him the seventh-most fantasy points during the 11 weeks. His rushing efficiency was good (4.70 YPC, 1.88 YAC) and his receiving efficiency was elite (his 6.8 YPT ranked fifth among RBs -- his fourth-career top-six finish in the category). Johnson is now 29 years old and the Houston offense has some uncertainty with Deshaun Watson's future in question, but he should lead a Houston backfield that also includes Phillip Lindsay and Mark Ingram in touches. Expect Johnson to flirt with flex numbers.

outlooksByWeek.1: The No. 1 overall pick, Lawrence makes his NFL debut against a Texans defense that hasn't threatened opposing offenses for some time. With a great supporting cast in what should be a high-volume Jaguars offense, we project Lawrence to be a low-end QB1 for fantasy purposes this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Lawrence was selected by Jacksonville with the first overall pick of April's draft. The Clemson product is an athletic 6-foot-5, 213 pounds with an outstanding arm. Lawrence's FBS passing efficiency stats don't jump off the page, but that shouldn't undermine his high-end potential, especially considering that his raw stats were incredible (90 TDs, 17 INTs in 40 games). Adding to Lawrence's appeal is his mobility, as he ran for 776 yards and 17 TDs over the past two seasons. Rookie QBs are rarely reliable fantasy starters, but Lawrence's mobility and a good group of targets led by DJ Chark, Laviska Shenault Jr., Marvin Jones Jr. and James Robinson gives him a shot to be an exception. He's worth a mid-to-late flier and obviously has QB1 upside in dynasty leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: White, coming off a somewhat disappointing 2020 season, shouldn't be forgotten. White isn’t a front-line fantasy play, but he's still more than capable of sucking up passing-down work, especially in Week 1 against a Miami defense that boasts a pair of great cornerbacks.

player.seasonOutlook: The 2020 season was White's first without Tom Brady and, not coincidentally, it resulted in his worst fantasy finish (42nd) since a 2014 rookie campaign in which he touched the ball 14 times. Despite the dud, White quietly ranked fourth at RB with a 16% target share (4.4 per game) and has been at or above 16% each of the past three seasons. He's finished no lower than 11th at RB in targets, receptions and receiving yards each of the past five seasons, but had 35 carries in 2020 and has never cleared 95 in a single season. The 29-year-old will defer nearly all rushing work to Damien Harris and Rhamondre Stevenson, but his huge receiving role keeps him in the deep league PPR flex discussion.

outlooksByWeek.1: Coming off a disappointing campaign in his first year with the Browns, Hooper has been somewhat of an overlooked commodity this summer. Nonetheless, the projection for this week's game against the Chiefs puts Hooper in low-end fantasy TE1 territory.

player.seasonOutlook: Hooper is entering his second season in Cleveland after failing to manage a top-20 fantasy campaign in 2020. The 2016 third-round pick had finished sixth in fantasy points in both 2018 and 2019 and actually averaged a career-high 19% target share in 2020, but Cleveland's early-season run-first scheme severely limited his volume and production. Hooper was primarily used as a short-area target (6.8 aDOT), which limited him to a career-low 6.3 YPT, and failed to clear four TDs for the fourth time in five seasons. Hooper did finish strong with three consecutive top-eight fantasy weeks as Cleveland opened up the passing game, so there's some sleeper appeal here. Consider him a late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Patriots defense boasts a strong secondary, but isn't as potent at the front-line and linebacker levels. Fantasy managers should expect "middle of the road" production here against Miami in Week 1 and act accordingly.

player.seasonOutlook: The post-Tom Brady Patriots took a big step back last season, so it may surprise you that their D/ST still managed its eighth top-12 fantasy campaign over the past nine seasons. The unit obviously fell off from its dominant first-place finish in 2019, but still showed well in several departments. The Patriots' 18 INTs paced the NFL for the second consecutive season and they ranked second in D/ST TDs (four) and seventh in points allowed (341). A majority of last season's unit is back for 2021 and a ton of talent was added to the mix, including Kyle Van Noy, Matthew Judon, Henry Anderson, Davon Godchaux and Jalen Mills. Dont'a Hightower (opt out) also returns to a unit with a loaded secondary and a ton of depth (though Stephon Gilmore will miss at least six weeks). Bill Belichick has rebuilt what should be a top-10 fantasy D/ST.

Myers was one of the best kickers in the NFL last season, nailing all 24 of his FG attempts. His accuracy has been inconsistent throughout his career, but he's now had two great seasons in the past three years (33-of-36 in 2018). He actually came out slow in 2020 with five consecutive games in single digits, but was the No. 2 kicker from Week 7 on. His 11 top-10 weeks for the season were most at the position. The 30-year-old is in a good spot as the kicker in a Russell Wilson-led offense, so he's back on the starting radar in 2021.

outlooksByWeek.1: Not even the bleached hairstyle helped Ertz find a new team this summer, as he'll play out the final year of his deal with Philadelphia. It's unclear just how much the Eagles will lean on Ertz, but he was plenty busy in the preseason and could surface as a streaming option for this first matchup.

player.seasonOutlook: Ertz is entering his ninth NFL season in search of a rebound after struggling with injuries, inefficiency and a shaky supporting cast during a very disappointing 2020. Ertz had ripped off five consecutive top-nine fantasy campaigns (including three straight top-four seasons) prior to missing five games and falling to 31st in 2020. Ertz played 81% of the snaps and handled a generous 19% of the targets during 11 active weeks, but 30% of balls thrown his way were off target (second highest), which led to a position-worst 49% catch rate and horrific 4.6 YPT (second worst). Ertz is "only" 30 years old, so a rebound is possible, but it's also reasonable to think his days as a TE1 are over, especially with Dallas Goedert likely ahead of him on the depth chart. Consider Ertz a mid-range TE2.

outlooksByWeek.1: McCaffrey produced at a prodigious rate in the three games in which he appeared last season. Despite a change at quarterback in Carolina, expecting his role and level of production to fall outside of fantasy RB1 territory -- including against the Jets Week 1 -- would be overthinking things way too much.

player.seasonOutlook: McCaffrey was limited to three games during an injury-plagued 2020, but the 25-year-old is well-positioned for a big bounceback this season. McCaffrey was fantasy's No. 2-scoring RB in 2018 before scoring an absurd 156 more points than any other back in 2019. He was on track for another dominant campaign last season, scoring exactly two TDs while posting 25-plus fantasy points in all three of his appearances. Even after the lost season, McCaffrey is one of the league's few remaining every-down backs and will benefit from Matt Rhule and Joe Brady's RB-friendly offense. McCaffrey is a candidate for 400 touches and locked in as the top asset in fantasy football.

outlooksByWeek.1: Taylor rushed for 1,169 yards and had 36 receptions for 299 yards in 2020. The Colts figure to lean on the run this season, and fantasy owners hope Taylor will be a bit more involved in the passing game as well. Taylor firmly projects as an RB1 this week and is startable in all leagues.

player.seasonOutlook: Taylor enters his second NFL season as the clear lead back in Indianapolis. The 2020 second-round pick's rookie season got off to a very underwhelming start, as despite a Week 1 season-ending injury to Marlon Mack, Taylor was limited to one top-12 fantasy week in his first 10 games. The light went on from that point forward, however, as he finished 15th or better in each of his final six games. Taylor's efficiency was outstanding, as his 5.0 YPC ranked ninth, his 88% catch rate first and his 7.3 YPT second among backs. The return of Mack and presence of Nyheim Hines on passing downs will limit Taylor's ceiling a bit, but he's a 22-year-old super-athlete who was already third in rushing yards and sixth in fantasy points as a rookie. Taylor is a solid RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Those wondering how good Robinson could be with a better quarterback may finally get their answer, just not right away. Week 1 signal caller Andy Dalton should be an upgrade over last season, and eventually Justin Fields will be at the Bears helm. However, Robinson draws the Rams’ Jalen Ramsey in the opener, dropping him to WR2 status.

player.seasonOutlook: Robinson has yet to have the benefit of playing with a top-end QB, and yet he continues to deliver the goods. The 2014 second-round pick has put together back-to-back top-10 fantasy campaigns, finishing no lower than sixth in targets and routes during each of the past two seasons. Robinson's 1,250 receiving yards in 2020 were his most since 2015 and, though he had some bad luck in the TD department (6 TDs, 7.8 OTD), his 15 end zone targets were third-most in the NFL. It's not a lock, of course, but Chicago's QB situation could be much better this season if first-round pick Justin Fields proves to be the real deal. Even if he doesn't, Andy Dalton may be an improvement on last year's situation. Robinson is in his prime at 28 years old and is one of the game's top talents. He's a borderline WR1 in fantasy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Sixth among backs in yards per route run last season, Swift might need to be an effective and efficient receiver to really take off as a fantasy option. The good news is that Swift has been cleared to play this week after dealing with a groin injury throughout camp. Per this initial matchup, the 49ers allowed 72 catches to backs last season, aiding Swift's case as a fantasy starter.

player.seasonOutlook: Swift enters his second NFL season as the clear lead back in Detroit. The 2020 second-round pick was limited to 114 carries in 13 games as a rookie, but was busy as a receiver, ranking no lower than 13th in targets, receptions, receiving yards, catch rate and YPT. Interestingly, Swift handled at least four targets in 11 games, but never had more than five in a single outing. Swift scored on an unsustainable eight of 114 carries as a rookie, but with newcomer Jamaal Williams second in line for touches, he's a strong bet to offset TD regression to the mean with a much larger workload in his second season. Even in a rebuilding Detroit offense, Swift has the look of a RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: It will be interesting to see if a preseason hamstring hampers Aiyuk at all in the opener against Detroit. If he's all good, this second-year breakout candidate could thrive against a Lions secondary that allowed the third-most fantasy points to receivers last season.

player.seasonOutlook: The 2020 49ers' offense was so overwhelmed with injuries that Aiyuk - a rookie - missed four games and still finished first among the team's non-linemen in offensive snaps. Seriously. Aiyuk posted a 60-748-5 receiving line and added 77 yards and two TDs on six carries during 12 active weeks, which was enough for the ninth-most fantasy points among WRs during that span. Aiyuk, who averaged 12.6 targets per game during a five-game stretch late in the season, may see a dip in usage with Deebo Samuel and George Kittle (among others) now healthy, but the 2020 first-round pick certainly looked the part as a rookie. Consider him a WR3 with upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Before suffering a season-ending ankle injury, Prescott led the NFL with 1,856 passing yards through Week 5 last season. While a 6,000-yard campaign isn't a likely outcome as he returns to action this year, it's clear Prescott is the offensive engine for Dallas against this capable Tampa Bay defense.

player.seasonOutlook: Following years of drama, Prescott finally signed a long-term extension with Dallas during the offseason. The 28-year-old took his game to another level back in 2019, totaling a career-high 33 TDs while finishing second in fantasy points among QBs. He was well on his way to an even better season in 2020, with 12 scores and sitting second in fantasy points in four games prior to suffering a season-ending ankle injury in Week 5. Prescott returns to arguably the league's best supporting cast, powered by the likes of Amari Cooper, CeeDee Lamb, Michael Gallup, Ezekiel Elliott and a very good offensive line. Prescott is, at worst, a solid weekly starter and has the upside to lead the position in fantasy points.

outlooksByWeek.1: An ankle injury curtailed Fant’s production last season, but he exhibited enough early and late to be drafted a TE1 this season. That’s where he profiles this week as he’ll likely be one of Teddy Bridgewater’s main targets when the Broncos take on the New York Giants in the Meadowlands to open the 2021 campaign.

player.seasonOutlook: Fant is entering his third NFL season having shown steady progress during his first two. The 2019 first-round pick impressed with a TE16 fantasy campaign as a rookie before making the leap to TE8 in 2020. Fant finished no lower than seventh at the position in targets, receptions and yardage. The only stumbling block for Fant has been finding paydirt, as he's scored three TDs in both seasons (3.4 OTD and four end zone targets in 2020). Perhaps that will improve this season, but Denver's run-first scheme, unsettled QB situation and crowded WR room could limit Fant's output. Despite the roadblocks, Fant appears to be the real deal, ranking first at TE in RAC as a rookie and fourth in 2020. The 23-year-old is a back-end TE1.

outlooksByWeek.1: With Travis Etienne's season-ending injury, the receiving workload that the rookie running back was expected to see is now going elsewhere. Shenault sits atop the list of candidates to fill that role. In Week 1, he'll fill it against the Texans. We view him as a solid WR3 candidate.

player.seasonOutlook: He didn't get much attention due to Jacksonville's struggles, but Shenault enjoyed a successful rookie campaign. The 2020 second-round pick missed nearly three full games but was WR28 in fantasy points during the 13 weeks he played in full. The versatile Shenault produced 600 yards and five TDs on 58 receptions and added 91 yards on 18 rushes. His 6.0 aDOT was third lowest among WRs, but he made up yards with his post-catch ability (5.2 RAC ranked 18th). The 22-year-old played an expanded role late last season (8.3 targets per game after Week 13) and is a strong bet for a second-year leap with coach Urban Meyer and QB Trevor Lawrence added to the fold. Shenault is a good flex target, and a full-on breakout is possible.

outlooksByWeek.1: Chark sat out the bulk of Jacksonville's training camp following finger surgery in early August. Still, he's expected to be available for the Week 1 game against the Texans. Given the favorable matchup for the Jaguars, Chark is a viable but risky WR3 candidate, should he end up starting.

player.seasonOutlook: Chark is back for his fourth season after what has thus far been an up-and-down NFL career. After barely playing as a second-round rookie in 2018, Chark broke out with a 73-1,008-8 receiving line and 17th-place fantasy finish in 2019. Injuries (three missed games) and weak QB play (Chark's 27% off-target rate was third most among WRs) struck in 2020, limiting Chark to three top-30 fantasy weeks. Chark is still only 24 years old and a candidate for a rebound season with a new coaching staff led by Urban Meyer and a new QB (Trevor Lawrence) in house. The speedy, 6-foot-3 perimeter receiver will need to fend off Laviska Shenault Jr. and Marvin Jones Jr. for No. 1 duties, but it's safe to value him as a fringe WR3.

outlooksByWeek.1: Turns out this Canton-bound receiver still has it; as Brown found his way back into the league and earned a Super Bowl ring to go with it last season. With a strong target share last season and plenty of buzz from camp, Brown could produce flex-worthy numbers against Dallas this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Brown re-signed with the Buccaneers after his tumultuous year-plus out of the league came to end when he joined the team in Week 9 last season. Including a trio of playoff showings, Brown appeared in 10 games along with Chris Godwin and Mike Evans and averaged 5.9 targets (16% share). His fantasy point total during the span extrapolated over 16 games (177.6) would've ranked 38th during the regular season. A WR-high 24% of his targets were screens, which limited Brown's yardage, but he didn't drop a ball and was great after the catch (5.8 RAC). The 33-year-old is third in line for targets behind Evans and Godwin in a high-scoring offense, so he's certainly on the flex radar in 12-team leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Hines, who rushed for 380 yards and had 64 receptions for 482 yards in 2020, will see plenty of targets in a game where Indianapolis is likely to be trailing. However, without much work on the ground he does not project as a starting-caliber running back this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Hines has carved out a role as a solid change-of-pace and receiving back during his three NFL seasons. The 2018 fourth-round pick ranks sixth among RBs in targets (217), receptions (170) and receiving yards (1227) since he entered the league, though his 5-foot-8, 198-pound frame has limited him to 226 carries (50th-most) and a weak 4.0 YPC during the same timeframe. Hines posted a career-best 15th-place finish in fantasy points last season, but his already-small role as a rusher, especially at the goal line, may shrink further with Jonathan Taylor emerging into a superstar and Marlon Mack back healthy. Hines has some deep-league PPR flex appeal, but that's about where the 24-year-old maxes out.

outlooksByWeek.1: Slated for the slot role that's led to some dominant play over the years in New England, Meyer could be leaned on heavily by rookie QB Mac Jones. While his double-digit projection for this week makes him playable, it doesn't demand that you roll with Meyer against a strong Miami secondary.

player.seasonOutlook: Meyers barely saw the field during his first year-plus in the league, but that changed when Julian Edelman went down for the season in Week 7 last season. Meyers took over and racked up 81 targets (a massive 30% team share) while playing 96% of the offensive snaps during the team's final 11 games. The 2019 UDFA signing was WR22 in fantasy during that stretch, bizarrely failing to catch a TD, but throwing two. Edelman retired, but Meyers has more competition for targets this season via newcomers Nelson Agholor, Kendrick Bourne, Hunter Henry and Jonnu Smith. Meyers struggled for fantasy relevance on last year's massive target share, but the 24-year-old will benefit from a more pass-friendly scheme with Cam Newton out and Mac Jones in at quarterback. He's a flex option in PPR formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: With T.Y. Hilton beginning the year on the IR, Campbell moves up the Colts' WR depth chart. In fact, he is likely to be the No. 2 option for new QB Carson Wentz. As such, Campbell projects as a borderline flex play in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: The Colts selected Campbell in the second round of the 2019 draft, but the Ohio State product has appeared in nine of a possible 32 games due to injury. Campbell barely saw the field as a rookie (22 touches in seven games) but appeared to be on the verge of a breakout in 2020. Campbell played 83% of the snaps in Week 1 and put up 80 yards on seven touches before going down for the season in Week 2. Campbell remains a very intriguing post-hype sleeper, especially considering T.Y. Hilton is now 31 years old (and on IR to open the season) and Michael Pittman Jr. is an unproven commodity. Campbell is super fast (a 4.31 40-yard dash) and quick (a 4.03 short shuttle) with the ability to contribute from the slot, as a rusher and as a returner. Grab him for your bench.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tagovailoa heads into the Week 1 matchup against New England locked in as Miami's undisputed starter -- and he's not without upside. That said, fantasy managers should view him only as an option in 2-QB leagues unless and until his performance demands we elevate his status or the bye weeks  limit other options.

player.seasonOutlook: Tagovailoa is now the clear-cut starter in Miami following Ryan Fitzpatrick's offseason departure. The 2020 fifth-overall pick was in and out of the lineup during a bumpy rookie campaign, but ended up with 14 total TDs to five INTs and was QB15 in fantasy points during seven full games as a rookie. Tagovailoa's efficiency will need to improve, but he adds some value with his legs and has an improved supporting cast after Will Fuller V and Jaylen Waddle were added to a core that also includes DeVante Parker and Mike Gesicki. Tagovailoa isn't a sure thing, but he's well-positioned for a second-year breakout and shouldn't cost more than a late-round flier on draft day.

outlooksByWeek.1: Featuring the league's most dangerous edge rushers and a solid pair of cornerbacks, the Browns have the kind of disruptive playmakers needed to create turnovers and fantasy points. This unit should be a regular start for fantasy managers, including in Week 1 against the Chiefs.

player.seasonOutlook: The Browns' defense: an NFL juggernaut? It's not as crazy as it sounds.
