Cleveland's D/ST hasn't finished a season better than 15th in fantasy points since 2001 (seriously), but did take a step forward in 2020 by ranking second in forced fumbles (17) and near mid-pack in most other categories. Of course, the real key here is what is now a loaded unit on paper following an offseason overhaul. Gone are eight of the defense's top 10 players in terms of 2020 snaps, but Myles Garrett and Denzel Ward are the exceptions and newcomers include Jadeveon Clowney, John Johnson III, Troy Hill, Takk McKinley, Malik Jackson, Anthony Walker, first-round pick Greg Newsome II and 2020 COVID opt-out Andrew Billings. Youngsters Grant Delpit and Greedy Williams are also back from injuries. This is a loaded unit and potential top-10 fantasy D/ST.

Since the start of the 2017 season, Gano has converted 74 of 78 FG attempts. That 94.9% hit rate trails only Josh Lambo for best in the NFL and, if we adjust for distance, Gano is the league's most accurate kicker during the span. Gano is coming off the best season of his lengthy career, having converted 31 of 32 field goal attempts in 2020. Despite a struggling offense that tied for last in touchdowns, Gano's 32 FG attempts were 12th most. Gano is now 34 years old, but the combination of his elite accuracy and an improved Giants offense makes him a viable starter in fantasy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Locked in with our second-highest projection among wide receivers, Hill is the primary outside option for one of the NFL's most explosive offenses in Kansas City. Play him without exception against the Browns in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Hill's game is that of a big-play machine, which sometimes means boom/bust production, but he's been more consistent than you probably realize. His target shares during active weeks have been between 22% and 24% and his air-yard shares between 36% and 39% each of the past four seasons. He finished as a top-10 fantasy WR in 40% of his games last season (third best) and was worse than 30th only 20% of the time (second best). Hill continues to break math as it pertains to TDs (53 career offensive TDs, 31.4 OTD) and efficiency (career 2.5 YPRR), but the speedy, explosive and heavily utilized 27-year-old has shown no sign of slowing down. Last season's No. 2-scoring fantasy WR has a legitimate shot to take the top spot away from Adams in 2021.

outlooksByWeek.1: Allen made 100 receptions for 992 yards in 2020 and was one of the NFL's top target-getters after Justin Herbert took over QB duties for the Chargers last year. Still the Week 1 matchup against a strong Washington defense is difficult, though not enough to lower Allen beyond the WR1/WR2 range.

player.seasonOutlook: Another season, another strong campaign from Allen. The 2013 third-round pick missed two games but finished top-13 in targets, receptions, receiving yards and fantasy points for the fourth season in a row. Allen has settled in as a short-area target, posting a career-low 9.9 YPR in 2020, but he also averaged 10.5 targets per game (his highest since 2015) and matched a career-high with eight TDs last season. Now 29 years old, Allen's play could see a dip in the near future, but he remains the clear No. 1 target in an ascending Justin Herbert-led offense. Consider Allen a fringe WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season, few players had a greater impact down the stretch and into the fantasy playoffs as Montgomery as he eclipsed 100 yards from scrimmage while scoring at least one touchdown in each contest from Week 12 through Week 17. Montgomery has a tough draw in the Bears opener as Chicago travels to Los Angeles where Rams and last season’s top defense awaits, slotting him as a low-end RB1.

player.seasonOutlook: Montgomery enters his third NFL season after a terrific second half of 2020 vaulted him to a fourth-place finish in fantasy points. Montgomery's season started slowly, as he managed only top-12 fantasy week in nine games, but he took advantage of a huge workload and very light schedule after returning from injury in Week 12 and went on to post six-consecutive top-8 weeks to finish the season. Montgomery ranked 17th in touches (14.3 carries, 3.0 targets per game) and 25th in fantasy points during three weeks with a healthy Tarik Cohen, but was top-four in both categories (16.6 carries, 5.0 targets) once Cohen went down. Cohen is still not back, but Damien Williams and rookie Khalil Herbert were added, so combined with a much tougher schedule, Montgomery figures to return to earth. He's a fine RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Allen might need his legs against a Steelers defense that led the league in sacks and allowed the fewest fantasy points to passers last season. It helps then that no quarterback has more rushing touchdowns than Allen since the start of the 2018 season. In fact, he's ninth in the entire league in rushing scores since being drafted.

player.seasonOutlook: Allen was last season's top scoring fantasy QB thanks to a breakout in his third pro campaign. The 25-year-old ranked no lower than sixth among QBs in pass attempts, completions, passing yards, passing TDs, completion percentage and YPA. He also continued to deliver the goods with his legs, scoring at least eight rushing TDs for the third consecutive season. Buffalo operated the league's second pass-heaviest offense in 2020 and that philosophy doesn't figure to change much as long as Allen is under center. The 25-year-old has cemented himself as an elite fantasy QB.

outlooksByWeek.1: Sutton is on track to play Week 1 after tearing his ACL in 2020’s opening game. He played in the final preseason contest, catching a pair of balls from new quarterback Teddy Bridgewater, including a touchdown. Even so, Sutton’s snaps may be tempered early, relegating him to WR3/flex status.

player.seasonOutlook: The Broncos selected Sutton in the second round of the 2018 draft, and the SMU product was well on his way to asserting himself as the team's No. 1 WR prior to an injury-plagued 2020 campaign that limited him to 30 snaps. Back in 2019, Sutton posted a 72-1,112-6 receiving line en route to a WR19 fantasy campaign. He was terrific after the catch (5.0 RAC), reliable (only two drops on 124 targets), and productive despite some bad TD luck (6 TDs, 7.2 OTD). During his first two seasons, Sutton ranked sixth in the NFL with 23 end zone targets. The presence of Jerry Jeudy, Noah Fant, KJ Hamler, Tim Patrick, Melvin Gordon and Javonte Williams may limit Sutton's upside, but the 25-year-old looked like a budding star before his injury. He's a WR3.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season, Cooks turned in his fifth 1,000-yard season over the last six years. That resulted in a mid-range WR2 finish, the same range for which he should be considered in 2021. He does have some upside going up against the Jaguars in Week 1, but don't bank on it.

player.seasonOutlook: Cooks has played for four teams in seven NFL seasons and has posted at least one top-17 fantasy campaign at all four stops. That's impressive. The 2014 first-round pick delivered the goods in Houston in 2020, averaging a career-high 24% target share, ranking 12th at the position with a 9.7 YPT and handling a career-high nine end zone targets. Despite some concussion concerns, Cooks has missed a grand total of three regular-season games over the past six seasons. With Will Fuller gone, 27-year-old Cooks is Houston's clear No. 1 WR, but his value could take a hit with Deshaun Watson's future in doubt. Cook has the look of a WR2 with Watson but will be more of a WR3 if Tyrod Taylor is at the controls.

outlooksByWeek.1: Michel’s role has yet to be determined but he’s expected to play a part in the Rams passing game as well as possibly see some red zone action. Darrell Henderson Jr. is still the lead back, but Michel should play enough to warrant flex consideration in deep leagues, despite drawing a tough Bears defense for his Rams debut.

player.seasonOutlook: Michel was traded to the Rams after playing only 31% of the Patriots' offensive snaps across three seasons after being selected in the first round of the 2018 draft. Some of that is injury related (including seven missed games in 2020), but it's also a product of scheme (he's a non-factor in passing situations with 40 career targets). Michel has run the ball pretty well and that includes a 5.7 YPC (second best) and 2.4 YAC (third best) on 79 carries in 2020. Despite already reaching 200-plus carries in two seasons, Michel has yet to post a top-30 fantasy campaign due to his lack of targets. The 26-year-old will share work with Darrell Henderson in Los Angeles, but he certainly has a path to a career-high workload in his first contract year. Michel is worth a look in the middle rounds, as he has RB2 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: A summer of hype gave way to a quiet camp for Goedert, especially as the continued presence of Zach Ertz looms large. Goedert was still a borderline TE1 working with Jalen Hurts with Ertz on the team last season, but both the ceiling and floor are lowered heading into this game against Atlanta.

player.seasonOutlook: Goedert played at least 80% of the Eagles' snaps in nine games last season. He handled a 19% target share (6.8 per game) those weeks and a 42-479-3 receiving line was enough for the third-most fantasy points at the position. Goedert missed five games due to injury, which limited his overall output, but he's now finished top-11 in fantasy PPG each of the past two seasons. He enters his fourth NFL season in a new (albeit still TE-friendly) scheme and appears to have taken the team's No. 1 TE gig away from Zach Ertz. The 26-year-old is positioned as an every-down player in an offense that has one of the league's most inexperienced WR rooms. Consider Goedert a mid-to-back-end TE1.

outlooksByWeek.1: There's not much upside in the Jets backfield, but Carter's playmaking ability is intriguing. He's worth rostering and watching as a potential receiving threat in this offense. Still, consider him to be outside of starting territory against the Panthers in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: The Jets selected Carter in the fourth round of April's draft. The North Carolina product is on the small side at 5-foot-8, 201 pounds, but is quick, explosive and a terrific pass catching prospect. Carter was very effective in 2020, averaging 8.0 YPC and running for 10-plus yards on 23% of his carries (both best in this year's class). Carter's lack of size and speed could limit him to a change-of-pace/kick returner role in the pros, but he has a path to lead back duties in New York with Tevin Coleman, Ty Johnson and La'Mical Perine his top competition. Carter's pass-catching prowess and path to a big snap share launches him into immediate weekly flex consideration.

Fields was selected by Chicago with the 11th overall pick of April's draft. The Ohio State product checks in at 6-foot-3, 227 pounds with outstanding accuracy, a good arm and high-end rushing ability. The latter sets him apart (81-383-5 rushing line in 2020), but Fields has also shown to be an aggressive and effective passer. His 10.3 average depth of throw and 91 total QBR are both tops in this year's rookie class over the past three seasons and he protected the ball well (1.5% INT rate). It's possible Andy Dalton will get a few starts to open 2021, but the history of first-round QBs suggests Fields will be under center very quickly. His elite rushing ability, powered by 4.45 wheels, could quickly launch him into fantasy relevance, so he'll be a fine late-round pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: In his rookie season, Mooney finished second on the club in targets, behind only Allen Robinson. He showed improvement as the season progressed and should pick up where he left off in his sophomore campaign. In Week 1, he may benefit if Jalen Ramsey shadows Robinson, but he’s still on the outside looking in with respect to viable fantasy receiver candidates.

player.seasonOutlook: Mooney was the 24th wide receiver selected in the 2020 draft, but the unheralded fifth-rounder ended his rookie campaign seventh in the class in targets and ninth in fantasy points. Mooney quickly locked down Chicago's No. 2 WR gig opposite Allen Robinson and ended up with a solid 61-631-4 line on 98 targets. Mooney's 61 receptions are tied with Tyreek Hill for fourth most all-time by a rookie not drafted in the first four rounds. His efficiency was poor (his 6.4 YPT was seventh lowest among 87 qualified WRs), but poor QB play was a major factor, as 23% of balls thrown his way were off target (14th highest). Mooney will play a similar - if not expanded - role in the same scheme with perhaps better QB play in 2021. Take a late flier.

Butker opened his NFL career with three consecutive top-seven fantasy campaigns, which included a first-place finish in 2019. In yet another shining example of why you never reach on a kicker in fantasy, he fell to 11th and managed only five top-10 weeks in 2020. Butker hit a career-high 92.6% of his FG attempts (25 of 27), but missed six of 54 extra points (88.9%). Despite the "down" season, Butker remains the kicker for an elite, Patrick Mahomes-led Chiefs offense, which makes the 26-year-old one of the most-appealing kickers at a position overloaded with randomness.

outlooksByWeek.1: The top wideout on a team that didn't invest much in the position this past offseason, Williams could eventually surface as a relevant fantasy option. Facing a healthy 49ers secondary isn't an ideal matchup, thus Williams is best considered a depth piece to open the season.

player.seasonOutlook: Williams is now with Detroit after missing the entire 2020 season with a torn labrum. The 2015 UDFA looked like a gem find by the Chargers when he posted a 69-1,059-7 receiving line and was WR18 in fantasy back in 2016. However, despite settling in as a respectable vertical threat (finished top-15 in YPT in four consecutive seasons), Williams hasn't posted a fantasy finish better than 45th since. Williams is positioned for a full-time role in rebuilding Detroit, which certainly makes the 29-year-old a deep sleeper. Even in an offense that should struggle in 2021, Williams is worth a late flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: Buffalo will want to get to Ben Roethlisberger quickly this week; the long-time Steelers quarterback is famous for having one of the fastest snap-to-release rates in the league. It helps then that the Bills were able to generate the league's fifth-highest pressure rate on passers last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Sean McDermott continues to get the job done, as the Buffalo D/ST has now ripped off three consecutive top-nine fantasy campaigns. The Bills have finished no lower than eighth in both INTs and forced fumbles each of the past four seasons but have struggled to generate sacks during the stretch and fell outside the top 13 in both yardage and points allowed last season. On paper, this is a good unit, with Tre'Davious White, Jordan Poyer and Micah Hyde leading a solid secondary and Jerry Hughes and Matt Milano joining youngsters Tremaine Edmunds and Ed Oliver in the front seven. The unit's top-10 players in 2020 snaps all remain on the roster. Buffalo's D/ST is a solid starting option in fantasy.

Cohen remains on the PUP list after tearing his ACL in Week 3 last season and will miss at least the first six weeks of 2021. Once back, he'll step back in as Chicago's change-of-pace and primary receiving back. His 190-pound frame has limited him to no more than 99 carries in a single season and a grand total of four carries inside the 5-yard line. However, 70-plus catches in both 2018 and 2019 helped him to fantasy finishes of 11th in 2018 and 27th in 2019. During his first three seasons in the NFL, Cohen ranked fourth among backs in both targets (261) and receptions (203). The 26-year-old's efficiency was poor in 2019 (3.3 YPC, 4.4 YPT), he didn't impress pre-injury in 2020 (115 yards on 20 touches) and, following David Montgomery's breakout, he'll remain very limited as a rusher and at the goal line. Cohen will eventually return to PPR flex value in deep leagues, but his ceiling is low.

outlooksByWeek.1: Graham will likely share tight end duties with upstart sophomore Cole Kmet to begin the season but don’t be surprised if the split leans to the younger and more athletic Kmet as the season progresses. Graham will likely remain the bigger red-zone threat, but with the unpredictability of touchdowns, he’s no longer in the fantasy mix.

player.seasonOutlook: Graham is entering his 12th NFL season. He's now 34 years old, but remains a reliable player, having appeared in 16 games seven of the past eight seasons. Graham was a weapon near the goal line for Chicago last season, ranking fourth at TE in TDs (eight) and second in end zone targets (12). That allowed a 13th-place finish in fantasy points, though his playing time and targets did dwindle as the team got rookie Cole Kmet work in the second half of the season. Graham handled 6.1 targets per game during his first nine games, but 3.0 per game in the final seven. Graham will hit for the occasional TD, but his days as a consistent target and fantasy TE are likely over. He doesn't need to be drafted.

outlooksByWeek.1: Williams opted out of the 2020 campaign and after the Kansas City Chiefs released him, Williams landed with the Bears. He’ll back up James Montgomery and  compete with Tarik Cohen for third down duties once Cohen returns from the PUP list. It will take an injury to Montgomery for Williams to be fantasy relevant.

player.seasonOutlook: Williams signed with the Bears after opting out in 2020. The 29-year-old was no more than a change-of-pace back during his first four NFL seasons (all with Miami), but made a big leap in Kansas City. Consider: Williams played at least 49% of the snaps in 16 games with the Chiefs. He handled 13.3 carries and 5.3 targets per game during those weeks, which has allowed him 278 touches for 1534 yards and 21 TDs. His numbers add up to 340.4 fantasy points, which would have ranked second to only Alvin Kamara last season. Unfortunately, Williams is ticketed for clear backup duties in Chicago, with David Montgomery and eventually Tarik Cohen in the mix. Williams is only worth a late pick in deep leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Trivia time: Name the receiver who led the NFL with eight games of at least 100 receiving yards last season? It's impressive you guessed Ridley. Being the clear top target of an efficient quarterback against a suspect Philadelphia pass defense is a nice recipe for success.

player.seasonOutlook: After spending his first two seasons in Julio Jones' shadow (resulting in zero top-20 fantasy campaigns), Ridley finished no lower than ninth among WRs in targets, receiving yards, TDs and end zone targets in 2020. He was fantasy's No. 5-scoring WR. During the seven games Jones missed completely, Ridley managed a 31% share (11.9) and was WR3 in fantasy. That's notable with Jones now in Tennessee.  Ridley is now Matt Ryan's unquestioned top option, with the 26-year-old's top competition for targets rookie TE Kyle Pitts. Arthur Smith's run-oriented scheme could cut Ridley's volume, but the 2018 first-round pick should still deliver fringe top-5 WR numbers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Just 140 rushing yards shy of joining Eddie George, Earl Campbell, and Chris Johnson in the franchise's 6,000-yard club, Henry is a safe bet for over 20 totes against an Arizona defense that allowed just over 2,000 rushing yards last season.

player.seasonOutlook: As if Henry's 303-1540-16 rushing line in 2019 wasn't good enough, the oversized superstar back posted an incredible 378-2027-17 line on the ground last season. He's now led the league in carries, rushing yards and rushing TDs each of the past two seasons. He finished both seasons as a top-five fantasy back despite totaling 55 targets during the span. The lack of receiving work does lead to the occasional bust week, as Henry finished outside the top-30 RBs four times last season. Henry is now 27 years old, but has shown no sign of slowing down, having finished no lower than ninth in YAC each of the past four seasons. He's a solid RB1 in PPR and an elite play in non-PPR formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: A new coaching staff might just continue to use Sanders the way he was under the previous regime; an early-down force without a ton of upside in the passing game. The Falcons were solid against the rush last season, but the presence of an elite rushing quarterback might just help Sanders find some room.

player.seasonOutlook: Sanders returns as the feature back in Philadelphia after an injury-plagued, but productive 2020 campaign. The 2019 second-round pick missed nearly five full games, but averaged 14.1 carries and 4.6 targets per game during the 11 weeks he was a full go. He was RB11 in fantasy points those weeks and his 5.3 YPC for the season was second-best among backs. Sanders is only 24 years old, a capable receiver (he ranked seventh in receiving yards and second in YPT among RBs as a rookie) and won't be short volume in a Nick Sirianni scheme that has leaned heavily on the run the past two seasons. Sanders is a good RB2 with upside for more behind a good (and now healthy) Eagles' offensive line.

outlooksByWeek.1: From giving out route-running analysis on Instagram to juking teammates on Hard Knocks, it was an entertaining offseason for Cooper. Even as CeeDee Lamb has become the more coveted fantasy option by many accounts, Cooper is still a top target on a top passing attack. If there's any spot to exploit Tampa Bay's defense, it's at outside corner.

player.seasonOutlook: Cooper is undoubtedly one of the league's top WR talents, so it may surprise you to know that the six-year NFL vet has yet to finish a season better than 10th in fantasy points. Volume is the primary culprit, as he's never exceeded a 23% target share or 130 targets in a single season. Despite the capped ceiling, Cooper has finished as a top-21 fantasy WR in five of six seasons, including each of the past three. The 27-year-old was fifth among wideouts in Dak Prescott's five starts last season and figures to pick up where he left off in Dallas' high-volume, loaded offense in 2021. Cooper is a solid WR2 with the potential for a career-best season.

outlooksByWeek.1: The good news is that Hockenson enters the season healthy and with a sizable share of the Detroit passing game. Not as good is this matchup with a San Francisco defense that allowed the fewest fantasy points to tight ends in 2020. Then again, volume often helps offset matchup concerns.

player.seasonOutlook: Hockenson is yet another example of fading high-pedigree rookie TEs before jumping on the bandwagon in Year 2. The 2019 first-round pick posted a modest 32-367-2 receiving line in 12 games as a rookie before making the leap to a 67-723-6 line in 16 games in 2020. Hockenson finished no lower than fifth among TEs in fantasy points, targets, receptions and yardage, and no lower than 10th in routes, TDs and end zone targets. Detroit changed systems and QBs during the offseason, but also overhauled (not in the good way) at wide receiver. Hockenson's trajectory remains on the upswing at age-24 and, even in a rebuilding Detroit offense, he can be viewed as a solid fantasy TE1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Murray is second only to Lamar Jackson with nine performances of at least 200 yards passing and 40 yards rushing the last two seasons. Murray is in an ideal position this week against a Titans defense that allowed the fourth-most passing yards last season. This is also a game that has one of the highest totals of the week.

player.seasonOutlook: Murray has been as advertised since being drafted by Arizona with the first overall pick back in 2019. The 24-year-old has ranked top 10 in pass attempts and top 3 in rushing attempts among QBs during both of his two NFL seasons. He took a big step forward in 2020, improving his TD total from 24 to 37 while leaping from eighth to third in fantasy points. Murray will continue to see plenty of passing volume in an Arizona scheme that has led the NFL in pace of play each of the past two seasons and his elite rushing ability (133-819-11 in 2020) locks him in as a strong fantasy QB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Fuller has been dealing with a lower body injury that has kept him out of preseason action for the last few weeks. He is unable to play in Week 1 as he serves the final game of his four-game suspension, carried over from last year. He should be able to make his Dolphins debut in Week 2 against the Bills.

player.seasonOutlook: Fuller signed with Miami after spending his first five NFL seasons in Houston. The 2016 first-round pick flashed his upside often but battled injuries during his first four NFL seasons, missing 22 games during that span. He was well on his way to a breakout 2020, sitting eighth at WR in fantasy points with a 53-879-8 receiving line and a league-high 11.4 YPT prior to being suspended for the season's final five weeks (he'll complete the suspension in Week 1 this season). Fuller has plenty of competition for work (DeVante Parker, Jaylen Waddle, Mike Gesicki), but he's the best of the bunch and should be in the vicinity of the 6-to-7 targets per game he's averaged throughout his career. Fuller is a good WR3 target and could jump even higher if QB Tua Tagovailoa makes a second-year leap.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tampa Bay is taking a committee approach to the backfield once again this season, with Fournette competing with Ronald Jones II for early-down work. The presence of Gio Bernard limits Fournette's receiving, and thus fantasy, potential, for this matchup with the Cowboys.

player.seasonOutlook: Fournette was a star for the Buccaneers during last season's Super Bowl run, but his season was one of ups-and-downs as he shared the backfield with Ronald Jones II. The two played 12 "full" games together, with Fournette handling more snaps (419 to 296) and targets (56 to 23), but with Jones leading in carries (132 to 114). Tampa Bay re-signed Fournette during the offseason, so combined with his expanded role in the playoffs, the 26-year-old is a good bet to lead this backfield in 2021. That said, Jones is the more effective rusher and Giovani Bernard was added as a passing-down option, which is certain to limit Fournette's upside. Fournette has two-career top-10 fantasy campaigns, but is best-viewed as a RB3/flex option in 2021.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brown nursed a sore hamstring for most of the pre-season but enters Week 1 healthy with a full week of practice under his belt. Brown should again see around 100 targets as the top Ravens wideout. However, he has big play ability, so he'll most often land as an WR3 where he resides against the leaky Raiders secondary to open the campaign.

player.seasonOutlook: Baltimore's offensive scheme is about as unfriendly to WRs as they come, and Brown has felt the wrath during his first two NFL seasons. The 2019 first-round pick saw a big uptick in usage last season, playing 78% of the snaps, and handling 25% of Baltimore's targets (10th highest among WRs) and 38% of its air yards. He was targeted at least six times in 12 of 16 regular-season games. Despite the heavy usage - and a respectable eight TDs - Brown finished 35th at WR in targets, 42nd in receptions and 40th in yards. He was WR36 in fantasy, and 14th was his best weekly finish. Baltimore may throw more in 2021, but he's a candidate for fewer targets with Sammy Watkins, Tylan Wallace and eventually Rashod Bateman added to the mix. Brown is a flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Williams has always had big-play ability, and there may be a few more targets to be had with Hunter Henry out of the mix in Los Angeles for 2021. The Week 1 matchup against a strong Washington defense is difficult, making Williams a borderline flex play this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Williams is entering his fifth NFL season but has yet to deliver a top-30 fantasy campaign. The seventh-overall pick back in 2017, Williams has been a mainstay opposite Keenan Allen the past three seasons but has struggled for target volume (he has yet to clear 91 in a season) and consistent TD production (10 TDs in 2018, but seven total the past two seasons). Williams has settled in as a de facto situational deep threat, having ranked no lower than ninth in aDOT and 11th in YPR each of the past three seasons. The 26-year-old was limited to four top-35 fantasy weeks last season. Perhaps Williams will get rolling in Los Angeles' new scheme and in Justin Herbert's second season, but he's best drafted for your bench in the late rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: With Will Fuller spending Week 1 serving out the remainder of his suspension, Parker is in prime position to be Miami's top downfield option against the Patriots. Consider him to be a fringe WR3/flex option in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Following a breakout 2019 campaign in which he posted a 72-1,202-9 receiving line en route to a WR11 fantasy campaign, Parker crashed back to earth in 2020. He missed two games, was held to a 63-793-4 line and finished 40th in fantasy points. He has now missed at least one game (13 total) and finished 40th or worse in fantasy points in five of his six seasons. Parker will have more competition for targets this season after Miami signed Will Fuller V and drafted Jaylen Waddle, and the team's QB situation is a question mark with unproven Tua Tagovailoa under center. The 28-year-old Parker will still play a sizable role, but there's enough risk here that he's best-valued as a flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Still a real threat down the seam and in the red zone, Gronkowski is a touchdown-or-bust type tight end for this initial matchup with the Cowboys.

player.seasonOutlook: Gronkowski made a triumphant return to the NFL last season, appearing in all 20 of Tampa Bay's games en route to a Super Bowl victory. During the regular season, Gronkowski lacked targets (4.8 per game), but made up for it (as usual) with downfield usage (he's finished all 10 of his seasons Top 10 in aDOT) and heavy volume near the goal line (he paced the position with 14 end zone targets). Gronkowski's routine disappearing act last season (six top-six fantasy weeks, but eight of 23rd or worse), coupled with the return of O.J. Howard (who out-targeted him 19 to 14 in four games together last season), suggests we should view the 32-year-old as a TD-dependent TE2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Penny will likely be the No. 2 running back for Seattle, but there are several other options on the roster and the overall situation remains murky. Penny should not be in fantasy lineups for Week 1 and probably beyond, at least until this backfield clarifies itself.

player.seasonOutlook: Penny has played 14% of the Seahawks' offensive snaps since being drafted in the first round of the 2018 draft. Injuries have been the culprit, as he was limited to 10 games in 2019 and only three in 2020. The good news is that Penny has shown well when active, averaging 5.1 YPC (sixth-best among 77 RBs with 150-plus carries since 2018) and 2.0 YAC (12th-best) on 161 career carries and 6.9 YPT on 23 career targets. The 25-year-old has some post-hype appeal, but he remains behind Chris Carson on Seattle's crowded depth chart, so he's worth no more than a late-round flier in deeper leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Colts D/ST finished 2020 as the No. 3 overall fantasy defense. They face a tough Week 1 matchup against an elite Seahawks offense. With such a quality opponent on tap, it's best to look elsewhere for your D/ST needs in the opener.

player.seasonOutlook: The Colts' D/ST was one of the breakout units of 2020, finishing third in fantasy points, which marks its first top-12 finish since 2013. Indianapolis' 12 top-10 weeks and six TDs led the league. The unit finished no lower than 12th in INTs, forced fumbles, sacks, yardage allowed and points allowed. The Colts did lose a few solid contributors in Anthony Walker, Denico Autry, Justin Houston and Malik Hooker during the offseason, which leaves them with a few voids, but stars DeForest Buckner, Darius Leonard, Kenny Moore and Xavier Rhodes remain in place. This D/ST figures to take a step back in 2021, but will be a streaming option when the matchup is right.

Gay was selected by Tampa Bay in the fifth round of the 2019 draft and was fantasy's No. 4 kicker as a rookie. However, his "success" was very volume based, as he missed eight of his 35 FG attempts and five of his 48 extra points. Gay was waived prior to the 2020 season, but landed with the Rams as a late-season injury replacement. He went on to make 14-of-16 FG attempts and all 16 PAT tries while posting the sixth-most fantasy points during seven active weeks. The 27-year-old isn't a sure thing, but he's in a good spot as the kicker in a Sean McVay offense. He'll be a fine fantasy starter if he hangs on to the job.

outlooksByWeek.1: Williams' value will come in the weeks when he's used near the goal line. Barring an injury to Clyde Edwards-Helaire, it's going difficult to divine which weeks those might end up arriving. As such, Williams isn't a viable fantasy starter against the Browns in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Williams is a 26-year-old former UDFA with 128 career regular season touches, but he's on the fantasy radar as the probable No. 2 back on the high-scoring Chiefs' depth chart (his top competition is Jerick McKinnon). Williams made some noise last season when he clearly outplayed Le'Veon Bell during three games Clyde Edwards-Helaire was sidelined. Williams more than doubled Bell in snaps, while racking up 210 yards on 38 touches, compared to 100 yards on 23 touches for Bell. The departure of Bell and Damien Williams sets up Darrel Williams as an intriguing insurance option behind the talented, but still unproven Edwards-Helaire. Williams will be well worth a bench spot in most formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: What could have been. Lamb led the Cowboys in receiving yardage and red zone targets when Dak Prescott was healthy last season, but his production took a hit once Andy Dalton took over. Lamb should be able to produce against a Buccaneers defense that struggled at times against the pass in 2020.

player.seasonOutlook: Lamb enjoyed a successful rookie season, racking up 1,017 yards and six TDs on 85 touches, but it could've been even better. Lamb posted a 29-433-2 receiving line and was WR11 in fantasy during Dak Prescott's five starts but managed a 45-502-3 line and was WR35 in 11 games after Prescott's knee injury. The good news is that Prescott - as well as Dallas' elite offensive line - is back healthy for 2021, which sets up Lamb for a big leap in his second season. The 2020 first-round pick and Dallas' primary slot WR is likely to see a boost from his 18% rookie-season target share in one of the league's fastest-moving offenses. Consider the 22-year-old a borderline WR1 with elite upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Already one of the busiest players in the game, with newcomer Jameis Winston at the Saints helm and star wideout Michael Thomas opening on the reserve/PUP list, Kamara will need to shoulder even more of the load. Despite New Orleans' home opener against the Green Bay Packers being moved to Jacksonville, Kamara should challenge for the most fantasy points in the opening week.

player.seasonOutlook: The top-scoring fantasy back of 2020, Kamara finished a position-best 80% of his outings as a top-10 RB. Kamara's role in Sean Payton's offense is about as clear and consistent as they come, as he's finished between 171 and 194 carries each of the past three seasons while posting reception totals of 81, 81, 81 and 83 during his four NFL campaigns. Kamara has yet to finish as season lower than fifth at RB in targets, receptions or receiving yards and has finished top-two in total TDs during three of four seasons. Kamara's outlook is clouded by Drew Brees' retirement, but his combination of usage and talent positions him for a run at his fifth-consecutive top-10 fantasy campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: While other quarterbacks have similar upside on any given Sunday, Mahomes gives fantasy managers as consistent a shot at having the No. 1 fantasy producer at his position as anybody in the NFL. Start and play him without concern against the Browns in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: If not for resting in Week 17 last season, Mahomes may have paced the QB position in fantasy points for the second time in three seasons. Regardless, the 25-year-old still managed his third straight elite showing, ranking top five in pass attempts, passing yards, passing TDs and YPA while also finishing 10th among QBs in rushing yards. Kansas City's overhauled offensive line should cure the pass-blocking woes that plagued the team during the Super Bowl loss and Mahomes will be working in the Chiefs' extremely pass-heavy scheme with the likes of Tyreek Hill and Travis Kelce at his disposal. The former league and Super Bowl MVP should be the first QB selected in your fantasy draft.

outlooksByWeek.1: There were off-season rumors that former OC Brian Schottenheimer was fired because Pete Carroll wanted to run the ball more. If true, that could bode well for Carson. Seattle is expected to beat the Colts in Week 1, which could lead to extra carries late, regardless of the run-pass split to that point. Consider Carson as a solid RB2 this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Carson re-signed with Seattle during the offseason and will enter 2021 as the team's feature back. Carson missed nearly six full games last season (he's yet to appear in more than 14 games in a single regular season), but was productive when healthy, sitting seventh at RB in fantasy points during 11 full weeks. Carson ranked 11th in rushing yards those weeks after finishing fifth each of the previous two seasons. He also handled a career-high 3.8 targets per game. At worst, Carson has delivered good RB2 numbers each of the past three seasons and Seattle is expected to lean more on the run under new OC Shane Waldron. The 26-year-old figures to miss a game or two, but he's an underrated RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: An awesome rookie season saw Higgins thrive against man coverage and build a real rapport with Joe Burrow along the way. The Vikings struggled on the outside in pass coverage last season, aiding Higgins' case as a solid WR3 this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Higgins appeared in 14 full games as a rookie, and the results were extremely positive. The 2020 second-round pick played 81% of the offensive snaps and handled a 21% target share (31% air yards) those weeks. Only 20 WRs had more fantasy points during that span despite Joe Burrow missing half the season. Higgins' best weekly finish was ninth in Week 10, but note that of his seven top-30 fantasy weeks, five came in his final seven full games with Burrow. The 6-foot-4 perimeter threat will have his QB back in 2021, but his upside took a bit of a hit when Cincinnati selected Ja'Marr Chase with the fifth pick of April's draft. Even with Chase and Tyler Boyd involved, 22-year-old Higgins still has a path to 7-8 targets per game and is a fine WR3 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Andrews again checks in as one of the top tight ends in the league, though there is a big drop from Travis Kelce and Darren Weller to the next tier. Still, Andrews is routinely a key cog in the Ravens passing game and is usually busy in the red zone. Look for Andrews to get off to a solid start as the Raiders allowed the most fantasy points to tight ends last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Andrews is heading into his fourth NFL season having posted back-to-back top-six fantasy campaigns. The 2018 third-round pick has never finished a season better than 19th at the position in pass routes, but benefits from a huge target share (25% in both 2019 and 2020), his role as a vertical target (Top 5 in aDOT each of the past three seasons) and tons goal line work (his 17 TDs are tied for first, his 15.1 OTD ranks second and his 23 end zone targets ranks first among TEs over the past two seasons). In 2020, Andrews missed a pair of games, but still tied for third with eight top-10 fantasy weeks. The 26-year-old is one of Lamar Jackson's top targets and locked in as a top-five fantasy TE.

Thomas is back as the Saints' No. 1 WR, but he's expected to miss at least five games to open the 2021 season due to injury. This comes after Thomas suffered through an injury-plagued 2020 campaign that saw the veteran wide receiver post a 40-438-0 receiving line in seven regular-season outings. It's a disappointing turn of events after a 2019 campaign in which he set the NFL single-season reception record while posting an incredible 149-1,725-9 receiving line on 185 targets. Thomas had finished four consecutive seasons as a top-seven fantasy WR before last year's debacle. The Saints' QB situation is a question mark for the first time in Thomas' career (and Drew Brees' retirement is sure to hurt his efficiency), but a hefty target share (once healthy) shouldn't be a problem for Thomas, considering the Saints' underwhelming situation behind him on the depth chart. The 28-year-old is a fine mid-round target as he'll be in the WR1 mix when on the field.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season, Gordon contended with Philip Lindsay for playing time; this year he’ll have to fend off second-round draft pick Javonte Williams. Gordon’s pass-catching skills weren’t utilized much last season but with Teddy Bridgewater at the helm, Gordon should be on the receiving end more often. Even so, splitting carries relegates Gordon to the flex tier.

player.seasonOutlook: Gordon had a successful first season in Denver in 2020, ranking ninth among backs in carries, rushing yards and TDs while finishing as RB14 in fantasy. Gordon was effective as a rusher (4.6 YPC, 1.9 YAC) and has now scored at least nine TDs in five-consecutive seasons. On the flip side, Gordon wasn't as involved as expected as a receiver (45 targets is his fewest since 2015) and struggled badly in that area (RB-worst 3.5 YPT). Durability remains a concern (he's missed at least two games in four of six NFL seasons) and the 28-year-old now has legitimate competition via second-round pick Javonte Williams. Gordon may lead the unit early on in the season, but figures to struggle for consistent RB2 numbers. He's a fine flex target in drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: After a 77-catch 2020, Samuel ended up missing all of camp with injuries. He is trending towards playing in Week 1, but even so, figures to only be a secondary option behind Terry McLaurin for Washington. Consider Samuel as a borderline flex play.

player.seasonOutlook: Samuel reunited with HC Ron Rivera and OC Scott Turner, who coached him during his first three seasons in Carolina, when he signed with Washington during the offseason. Samuel progressively improved from 126th to 49th to 36th in fantasy points during that span and had his best campaign (25th) in 2020, totaling 848 yards on 76 receptions and 200 yards on 41 carries. Interestingly, Samuel actually saw his routes, targets and TDs dip last season, but a huge increase in efficiency and rushing usage led to the big fantasy campaign. In fact, Samuel finished with just 13 fewer fantasy points than new teammate Terry McLaurin. Samuel will be no lower than third in line for targets behind McLaurin and Logan Thomas in what will be a much more explosive offense with Ryan Fitzpatrick. Samuel is a fine WR3/flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: Coming off a seemingly quiet 1,100-yard season from scrimmage, Jones is simply splitting too much to help fantasy teams to open the season. With Leonard Fournette and Giovani Bernard looking to establish roles in this offense, Jones is merely a bench option for this first game against Dallas.

player.seasonOutlook: Jones is entering his fourth NFL season having established himself as an effective rusher, but finds himself without a clear lead back role. The 2018 second-round pick shared the backfield with Leonard Fournette in 2020, with the duo playing 12 "full" games together. During those outings, Jones trailed his teammate in snaps (419 to 296) and targets (56 to 23), but led in carries (132 to 114). Jones has shown to be the better rusher of the two (his 5.1 YPC ranked seventh and his 2.4 YAC fourth among RBs), but Fournette isn't going away and Giovani Bernard is now in the mix for passing-down work. Jones will max out as a flex most weeks, but the 24-year-old is a very good insurance option in Tampa Bay's high-scoring offense.

outlooksByWeek.1: In 2020, Pittman had 40 receptions for 503 yards. Now, with T.Y. Hilton beginning the year on the IR, Pittman is likely to be the Colts' top target-getter, albeit in a run-first offense. Pittman projects as a borderline flex play this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Pittman missed three contests and was limited to 4.6 targets per game during a fairly uninspiring rookie campaign. The 2020 second-round pick was on the field for a hefty 78% of Indianapolis' offensive snaps when active, but he was held to a 40-503-1 receiving line and only two weekly fantasy finishes better than 50th. Pittman was mostly used in the short area (8.9 aDOT) but was terrific with the ball in his hands (his 6.9 RAC ranked third among WRs). The 23-year-old is a strong bet for a second-year leap as, with T.Y. Hilton out, he slots in opposite Zach Pascal, with Parris Campbell in the slot. The 6-foot-4 Pittman is a breakout candidate and a very good target for your flex spot.

outlooksByWeek.1: In one of the more valuable understudy roles in the league, Mattison won't see the field very much this week against the Bengals as long as Dalvin Cook is healthy.

player.seasonOutlook: Minnesota selected Mattison in the third round of the 2019 draft and the former Boise State star has done an admirable job backing up Dalvin Cook over the past two seasons (4.6 YPC, 1.9 YAC, 7.7 YPT). Mattison doesn't see the field much when Cook is healthy, but showed well with 277 yards and three TDs on 58 touches in three games in relief of an injured Cook in 2020. Only six RBs scored more fantasy points those weeks. Mattison has no standalone value, but especially after the departure of Mike Boone, the 23-year-old is locked in as one of fantasy's top insurance options. He'll be in the RB1 discussion if Cook (two-plus missed games in all four NFL seasons) misses more time.

outlooksByWeek.1: Crowder tested positive for COVID-19 late last week, putting his availability for New York's Week 1 tilt against the Panthers in question. If available, Crowder will be part of the Jets' three-man rotation at wideout. Even so, he'd still be well outside of starting territory for fantasy managers.

player.seasonOutlook: Crowder has been one of the league's busiest wide receivers during his two seasons with the Jets, ranking top-13 in average target share in both 2019 and 2020. The heavy usage allowed Crowder a WR26 fantasy campaign in 2019, and he was WR14 during 12 active weeks in 2020. Despite the success, Crowder is a good bet for a step back in 2021. His usage and production declined as last season progressed (11.5 targets per game in his first four games, 5.5 in his final eight), New York will have a new coaching staff and rookie QB (Zach Wilson), and the Jets added Corey Davis, Elijah Moore and Keelan Cole to the WR room. Crowder is a short-range target in a low-scoring offense. The 28-year-old is a PPR flex in 12-team leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Vikings' defense just couldn't get to the pocket last season. The return of Danielle Hunter should help increase the team's pressure rate, as should this matchup against a patchwork Bengals offensive line.

player.seasonOutlook: The Vikings' D/ST was one of the biggest disappointments of 2020, plummeting to a 27th-place finish after six consecutive seasons finishing 13th or better (including three top-fives the past four years). The big culprits were sacks, yardage allowed and points allowed, as Minnesota finished 27th or worse in all three categories while also failing to score a single D/ST TD. On the plus side, the Vikings' 15 INTs ranked seventh. Expect defensive mastermind Mike Zimmer to lead this group to a better showing in 2021. Patrick Peterson, Dalvin Tomlinson, Mackenzie Alexander and Xavier Woods were added to a unit that will have Michael Pierce, Danielle Hunter and Anthony Barr back after the trio missed all or most of 2020. Add Eric Kendricks and Harrison Smith to the mix and Minnesota's D/ST has the talent to leap back into weekly starting consideration.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jacksonville's first-round pick suffered a Lisfranc injury during the preseason and will not play for the team this season. Dynasty-leaguers can certainly stash the running back for the future, but those fantasy managers playing in one-and-done leagues should let him go.

player.seasonOutlook: Etienne is out for the 2021 season with a foot injury. Etienne was selected by the Jaguars with the 25th pick of the 2021 draft and, once healthy, will join a backfield that also includes James Robinson. Etienne is arguably the most explosive back in this year's class and also brings speed and strong pass-catching ability to the table. He stands 5-foot-10, 215 pounds and was extremely productive during four years at Clemson, racking up 6,107 yards and 78 TDs on 788 touches. That includes 85 receptions over the past two seasons, which is most in this year's class. Etienne's elusiveness jumps off the page, as his 4.1 YAC ranks third and his 3.3 Forced Missed Tackle rate ranks sixth in this year's class over the past three seasons. Etienne will be 23 years old when he makes his NFL debut in 2022 and remains a strong dynasty hold.

outlooksByWeek.1: It helps that the Bengals allowed the second-most yards per carry to backs last season, but you don't need anyone to tell you to start Cook. We won't even say it. You already know it.

player.seasonOutlook: Cook returns as the feature back in Minnesota after a 2020 campaign in which he posted a career-best second-place finish in fantasy points among RBs. Despite missing two games, Cook ranked second at the position in carries, touches, scrimmage yards and TDs. His 22 carries inside the opponent's 5-yard line topped the NFL. Cook has finished top-three in fantasy points per game each of the past two seasons, but durability continues to elude him. He's missed at least two games in all four of his NFL seasons. Of course, when you're performing at an elite level, some missed time is tolerable. Cooks remains a top-three fantasy RB in a Vikings' offense that finished fifth in the NFL in TDs last season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Metcalf made 83 receptions for 1,303 yards in 2020. A faster-paced offense and more diverse route tree could help Metcalf earn even more total receptions, in addition to his big-play ability. Metcalf should find himself among the top-five wide receivers this week, and is as close to a WR1 lock as there is for Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Metcalf flashed in a big way as a second-round rookie back in 2019, but he took his game to the next level in 2020. The oversized perimeter threat finished 11th among WRs with 131 targets and sixth in routes (577), receiving yardage (1,303) and TDs (10). Metcalf's 15 end zone targets ranked third in the NFL, and his career mark of 34 in that category is five more than any other player since he entered the league. Metcalf finished 2020 seventh in fantasy points but didn't show quite the high ceiling we expected, as his three top-10 fantasy weeks ranked tied for 17th. Nonetheless, Metcalf is only 23 years old and one of the best athletes in the game. He's a solid WR1 with elite upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Travis Etienne's season-ending foot injury opens the door to a full workload for Robinson. That certainly worked out well for the undrafted free agent and fantasy managers last season. Make no mistake: consistent RB1 production is well within the range of possible outcomes, starting this week against the Texans.

player.seasonOutlook: It's not often that an undrafted free agent posts an RB1 campaign as a rookie, but Robinson made it happen in 2020. The Illinois State product replaced Leonard Fournette as the team's feature back and went on to finish seventh among RBs in both scrimmage yards and fantasy points despite missing two games. Robinson was a factor as a rusher (sixth in carries) and receiver (10th in targets) while playing 70% of the offensive snaps. Robinson is a candidate for TD regression to the mean (10 TDs, 5.9 OTD), but with Travis Etienne out for the season, the second-year back remains positioned for a substantial offensive role. Consider Robinson a mid-range RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: He has a new quarterback (Sam Darnold) this season, but Moore, who finished the 2020 season with just over 18 YPC (and came up just short of 1,200 total receiving yards), is a top asset in the Panthers receiving corps. Lock him in as a WR2, based on his anticipated role.

player.seasonOutlook: Back in 2019, Moore broke out with an 87-1,175-4 receiving line in what was his second NFL season. The 2018 first-round pick posted a similar line (66-1,193-4) in a new offense last season, though his usage was quite different. Moore handled more deep targets, which vaulted his aDOT from 11.2 to 13.6 and his YPT from 8.7 to 10.0 (ninth highest in the NFL) but crushed his catch rate (64% to 55%) and reception total. Moore also struggled with drops (eight) and continues to underwhelm in the TD department (10 in three seasons), but he sees plenty of volume (25% target share last season) and is one of the game's better young playmakers. The 24-year-old, who very well could get better QB play with Sam Darnold under center this season, should be valued as a fringe WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kupp, like most of his teammates, is coming off a down season. However, with Matthew Stafford at the helm, Kupp’s production should increase. In Week 1, he checks in as a low end WR2, high end WR3 with a tough Chicago Bears defense in town for Rams opener.

player.seasonOutlook: Kupp played 80% of the Rams' snaps, ran 82% of the routes and handled 8.3 targets per game in both 2019 and 2020. Despite the remarkable consistency, Kupp fell from fantasy WR4 in 2019 to WR26 in 2020. The primary culprit? Predictable TD regression to the mean. Kupp scored 10 TDs (5.4 OTD) in 2019 but managed only three (3.6 OTD) in 2020. Kupp's efficiency was otherwise pretty similar to years past, and he has now finished no lower than 13th at WR in receptions, RAC and catch rate each of the past two seasons. Kupp, who actually out-targeted Robert Woods 134 to 128 in 16 games together last season, is one of the game's top slot WRs and gets a boost from the team's QB upgrade to Matthew Stafford. Consider the 28-year-old a good WR3 in PPR.

outlooksByWeek.1: Los Angeles' new Offensive Coordinator Joe Lombardi has talked about running a faster-paced offense in 2021 that runs through Herbert. That means (potentially) lots of passing attempts from a guy who threw for 4,336 yards in 2020. Week 1 will be a challenge against what looks to be a very stout Washington defense. As such, Herbert projects as only a borderline QB1 this week.

player.seasonOutlook: It took a bizarre Tyrod Taylor injury to get him on the field, but Herbert quickly seized Los Angeles' starting job and didn't give it back during a very impressive rookie season. The 2020 sixth-overall pick accounted for 36 TDs and 10 INTs in 15 games, which helped him to a top-10 fantasy week in 60% of his starts. That trailed only Aaron Rodgers and Kyler Murray for tops at the position. Herbert's numbers certainly benefited from a very fast-moving and high-volume offense, but new OC Joe Lombardi's past offenses leaned heavily on the pass. Herbert looks like the real deal and he does enough with his legs to supply him with a high floor and a massive fantasy ceiling. Even with an underwhelming supporting cast, the 23-year-old is a viable QB1 with upside for more.

outlooksByWeek.1: Thomas figures to be the second or third option in a much-improved Washington offense in 2021. He is a solid TE1 choice for this week and is startable in all leagues.

player.seasonOutlook: Thomas was the breakout tight end of 2020, as the converted QB exploded for a 72-670-6 receiving line and a TE3 fantasy finish. He ended up pacing all tight ends in snaps and routes, and finished no lower than seventh in targets (108), receptions (72), yardage (670) and end zone targets (nine). Thomas' season started slowly despite a generous target share with Dwayne Haskins under center, but he bloomed down the stretch with Alex Smith. Perhaps his 19% target share will decrease with ultra-conservative Smith gone and Curtis Samuel added at WR, but that could easily be offset by more big plays and scoring opportunities courtesy of gunslinging QB Ryan Fitzpatrick. Thomas is well positioned for another TE1 campaign and the 29-year-old should be on your radar in the middle rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: Once an every-down threat for the Steelers, Conner is likely to serve as an early-down bruiser for the Cardinals. Conner does present some scoring upside as Arizona's potential goal-line back as he faces a Titans team that allowed a rushing touchdown to a running back in all but four games last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Conner signed with Arizona after spending his first four seasons with the Steelers. The 2017 third-round pick has missed at least three games each of the past three seasons and a total of 14 in his career. The Pitt product peaked with an RB6 fantasy finish in 2018, but he plummeted outside the top 25 each of the past two seasons. The 26-year-old is solid as both a rusher (career 4.3 YPC, 1.8 YAC) and receiver (6.3 YPT), but figures to focus primarily on the former as he takes over Kenyan Drake's role in Arizona. Drake ranked seventh among RBs in carries, eighth in rush TDs and third in carries inside the 5-yard line in 2020. Conner will defer most passing-down work to Chase Edmonds, but his new role keeps him in the RB3/flex mix.

outlooksByWeek.1: With Michael Thomas on the shelf for at least six weeks, Callaway parlayed a strong preseason into the top spot on the Saints receiver depth chart. Even so, while Jameis Winston may look to stretch the field more than the retired Drew Brees, Calloway is nothing more than a deep league flex as New Orleans hosts the Green Bay Packers, with the Week 1 affair moved to Jacksonville.

The No. 4 offense from last season added Julio Jones over the summer. Tannehill has set new highs in QBR in consecutive seasons since joining Titans. Even as he's working with a new offensive coordinator, Tannehill figures to shine against an Arizona defense that could prove exploitable at cornerback.

player.seasonOutlook: Tannehill took over as the Titans' starting QB in Week 7 of the 2019 season. He was fantasy's No. 3 QB from that point forward and followed that up by finishing seventh as the full-time starter in 2020. He's been nothing short of elite during the two campaigns, totaling 66 TDs and 13 INTs while completing 67% of his passes and averaging a league-best 8.6 YPA. The addition of Julio Jones helps offset the departures of Corey Davis, Jonnu Smith and Adam Humphries, but losing OC Arthur Smith is notable as well. This still figures to be a very run-heavy offense (Tannehill finished 18th in pass attempts last season), which limits the ceiling a bit. Even at 33 years old, Tannehill still adds value with his legs, which along with his strong efficiency, keeps him in the QB1 conversation.

outlooksByWeek.1: With Gerald Everett in Seattle, Higbee is the clear starter at tight end as Brycen Hopkins and Jacob Harris are still learning the position. Higbee is more of a floor play, but he should see sufficient targets with Matthew Stafford at the helm to be a low end TE1. In the Rams opener against the Bears, Higbee falls just outside of the top tier, making him a matchup play.

player.seasonOutlook: During the final five weeks of 2019, Higbee came out of nowhere to average 11.4 targets per game and was fantasy's top-scoring TE by 23 points. It appeared the cat was out of the bag and Higbee was finally in the TE1 mix. So much for that. Higbee posted a 44-521-5 receiving line in 2020 with three of those five scores coming in one game (he had a 43-522-2 line during those five weeks in 2019). Higbee is a good all-around player, but he's now 28 years old and Sean McVay doesn't seem interested in permanently increasing his passing-game usage. Perhaps Matthew Stafford will unlock his fantasy value, but even with Gerald Everett is gone, Higbee is an uninspiring TE2.

outlooksByWeek.1: He's suddenly the insurance policy for James Robinson in a Jacksonville backfield that lost Travis Etienne to a season-ending foot injury. Still, Hyde isn't a viable weekly play -- including this week against one of his former teams, the Texans.

player.seasonOutlook: Hyde is now on his second stop in Jacksonville after battling for work in Kansas City, Houston and Seattle the past two years. Hyde's first stop in Jacksonville was unsuccessful (62 touches in eight games in 2018), but that was, of course, a different regime, as the team has now hired Hyde's college coach, Urban Meyer. Hyde, who turns 30 this year, adds little as a receiver and is no longer feature back material, but makes for a solid backup. That's the role he's likely to play behind James Robinson this season. Hyde will only be on the fantasy radar if Robinson misses time.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Rams D/ST is one of the best units in the league and while they may not be matchup-proof, they're one opening week's top options with the Chicago Bears traveling to Los Angeles in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: The Rams' D/ST was the top-scoring unit by 12 fantasy points last season and has now posted finishes of fourth, third, ninth and first during Sean McVay's four seasons with the team. During its dominant 2020 campaign, the Rams allowed the fewest yards and points, while also ranking second in sacks (53) and D/ST TDs (four). Despite the success, this unit could be in for a step back in 2021. Defensive coordinator Brandon Staley departed for the Chargers and Michael Brockers, John Johnson III and Troy Hill (the latter two finished 1-2 in snaps last season) left via free agency. Of course, star power remains in the form of Jalen Ramsey and Aaron Donald, in addition to solid contributors like Leonard Floyd and Darious Williams. Consider the Rams D/ST a midrange starting option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Recovered from a quad issue which sidelined him for two weeks in August, Moore heads into New York's Week 1 game against the Panthers as a top-three option at wideout for the Jets. Still, with only a single-digit fantasy scoring projection, managers shouldn't force him into their lineups for Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: The Jets selected Moore with the 34th pick of April's draft. The Ole Miss product is an athletic 5-foot-9, 185-pound slot receiver with good speed and quickness. He has reliable hands and post-catch tackle-breaking ability but can also get deep for a big play. His size may limit his ability to play outside and beat press, but he has the look of a high-volume slot target who can help out as a rusher and returner. He aligned inside 92% of the time and handled a healthy 27% target share while posting a 91% adjusted catch rate during his final three FBS seasons. Moore's 2021 fantasy outlook is clouded by a rookie QB (Zach Wilson) and a very crowded WR room (Jamison Crowder, Corey Davis, Denzel Mims, Keelan Cole), but his pedigree makes him well worth a late-round flier.

Koo's NFL career got off to a slow start when he was cut after only four games with the Chargers back in 2017. After bouncing around the country for a few years, including a stop in the AAF, Koo finally found a home with the Falcons in 2019. Since that point, he's been one of the league's best kickers, nailing 60 of his 65 FG attempts (92.3%) and 48 of 53 extra points (90.6%). In 2020, Koo attempted 39 field goals (second most in the league) and converted 37 (most) for an impressive 94.9% conversion rate. He delivered 10 top-10 fantasy weeks (tied for second most) en route to finishing second among kickers in fantasy points. The 27-year-old is a solid fantasy starter.

outlooksByWeek.1: Edwards opens the 2021 season alongside fellow sophomore Henry Ruggs, with Edwards serving bigger, more physical wideout. Both will take a backseat to tight end Darren Waller with respect to targets, relegating Edward to the fantasy bench with the Ravens visiting Las Vegas in the season’s inaugural Monday night tilt.

Last season, Adams was on pace for one of, if not the best season from a wide receiver in history, but he missed two games. No wideout in the league is blessed with Adams’ combination of high floor and unlimited ceiling. With Aaron Rodgers back at helm, expect Adams to be the top-ranked wideout almost every week, which is where he sits Week 1 against the New Orleans Saints in what should be a high-scoring affair.

player.seasonOutlook: Adams was the top-scoring fantasy WR of 2020 by 29 points, which is incredible, considering he missed 2.5 games due to injury. Including a pair of playoff games, Adams was targeted at least nine times in 14 of his 15 full games and posted a ridiculous 130-1,471-20 receiving line during that span. He reached double-digit TDs for the fourth time in five seasons and posted a top-10 fantasy week in a position-best 57% of his regular-season outings. Adams averaged a career-high (and league-high) 34% target share, and he's now been at or above 30% each of the past three seasons. The 28-year-old hasn't appeared in 16 games in a regular season since 2016, but he's so good when active that we can deal with some missed time. Aaron Rodgers' top weapon is the best WR in fantasy.

outlooksByWeek.1: While J.D. McKissic will still get plenty of passing-game work, Gibson's talent is likely to lead to more targets -- and Peyton Barber's release could mean more carries as well. Gibson projects to be among the top-five runnong back this week, and is one of the best overall options to lean on.

player.seasonOutlook: Gibson is entering his second NFL season following an impressive rookie campaign in which he averaged 4.7 YPC on 170 carries. This after he totaled 33 carries in college. The third-round pick found the end zone 11 times (only six RBs had more), which helped him to five top-10 fantasy weeks (only five RBs had more). Gibson is a candidate for TD regression to the mean (7.0 OTD), but there is a lot of room for more touches after he only played 47% of the snaps during 13 full games. The 23-year-old is still pretty raw as a rusher and he's a very capable receiver as a former wide receiver. Assuming he takes on an expanded role in 2021, Gibson can be viewed as a good RB2 with massive upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: A touchdown magnet who has turned in at least 1,000 yards in every season of his career, Evans enters 2021 as arguably Tom Brady's most trusted red zone threat. Looking to Thursday evening, the Cowboys' outside corners could struggle with Evans' size.

player.seasonOutlook: Evans' first season with Tom Brady led to third-best fantasy finish of his seven-year career (11th). Evans' production was very reliant on TDs, however, as his 13 scores were a career high and fourth most at the position. Evans' 109 targets (24th) and 18% target share (49th) were career lows. Believe it or not, Evans has finished only one season better than ninth in fantasy points. Of course, at 6-foot-5 and having finished no lower than ninth in end zone targets every season of his career, Evans will rarely be short on TDs. Consider that in 10 "full" games with Chris Godwin and Antonio Brown, Evans led the trio with 73 targets (20% share) and his 16.1 fantasy PPG during the span extrapolated over 16 games would've ranked 10th during the regular season. The 28-year-old is a mid-range WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Even playing second fiddle to Nick Chubb, Hunt has proven to be remarkably productive for Cleveland. Play him with confidence as a low-end RB2 or high-end flex against the Chiefs in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Despite playing second fiddle to Nick Chubb for most of 2020, Hunt finished 12th or better among RBs in touches, yards, TDs and fantasy points. During 13 full games the two backs played together, Hunt trailed in snaps (451 to 391) and carries (215 to 136), but led in routes (183 to 175) and targets (41 to 29). Interestingly, Hunt was RB11 in fantasy during four games Chubb was out, but RB13 during the 11 regular season games both played in full. Hunt's ceiling will continue to be limited as long as Chubb is healthy, but he's very effective (Top 8 in YAC all three seasons with 100-plus carries), busy as a receiver and working behind an elite offensive line. The 26-year-old is a flex option and arguably the best insurance policy in fantasy.

Dobbins is out for the 2021 season with a torn ACL. Dobbins was set to enter his second NFL season after an impressive rookie campaign in which he paced the NFL in both yards per carry (6.0) and yards after contact (2.5). Granted the elite efficiency came on relatively low volume in Baltimore's committee attack (134 carries), but the second-round pick's production increased down the stretch. Dobbins averaged 7.4 fantasy PPG during his first nine NFL games before posting 13-plus points in six-consecutive games to finish the season (17.0 per game). A healthy Dobbins will be back on the RB2 radar in 2022.

outlooksByWeek.1: Gaskins' 2020 usage, which tended to be that of a true featured back, could be dialed back slightly this season. Until we better understand his role, playing him as a low-end RB2/flex against the Patriots in Week 1 would be the best approach.

player.seasonOutlook: Gaskin was one of the bigger surprises of the 2020 season, as the 2019 seventh-round pick won the team's lead back gig in camp and went on to play 69% of the team's offensive snaps when active. He was RB8 in fantasy those weeks. Gaskin was held without a top-20 fantasy week in his first four games before finishing no lower than 17th in his final six games. Gaskin was competent as a rusher, but exceptional as a receiver, finishing seventh among RBs in receiving yards thanks to an 87% catch rate (second best) and 8.3 YPT (best). Miami's only notable RB acquisition this offseason was Malcolm Brown, so Gaskin remains locked in as lead back. The 24-year-old is a borderline RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: A seemingly rough training camp marked by drops and some separation issues could lead to a slow start for Chase in the pros. Then again, he's a special prospect with a longstanding rapport with Joe Burrow. Even with the Vikings' struggles in pass coverage last season, Chase isn't yet a trusted play.

player.seasonOutlook: Chase was selected by the Bengals with the fifth-overall pick of April's draft. The LSU product is a versatile and physical 6-foot, 201-pound wideout with a laundry list of assets, including good strength, speed, hands, as well as ball-tracking and tackle-breaking ability. He opted out of the 2020 season, but he's only 21 years old and broke out at the young age of 19. The Bengals had a third WR on the field on 82% of their offensive plays in 2020 (2nd most in NFL), so playing time won't be an issue even with Tyler Boyd and Tee Higgins in the fold. Also, consider that since 2009, five of the six WRs picked Top 6 in the draft were top-30 fantasy WRs as rookies. Chase has elite upside and is immediately on the WR3 radar.

outlooksByWeek.1: The rise of the dual-threat quarterback continues with Hurts, who tallied elite fantasy production in his short stint as a starter last season. Now at the helm of a new-look offense, Hurts could continue his QB1 run with a matchup against an Atlanta defense that allowed the second-most fantasy points to quarterbacks in 2020.

player.seasonOutlook: Hurts is locked in as the Eagles' starter after Carson Wentz was traded to the Colts. Hurts appeared in three full games as a rookie, throwing for 847 yards and five TDs, while adding a 38/238/1 rushing line, outscoring all but two QBs in that short span. Hurts' efficiency will need to improve, though his 52% completion rate was distorted by a league-high 9.5 average depth of throw (the longer the pass, the lower the expected completion rate) and his 13.8 YPC paced the NFL, hinting at a worthwhile tradeoff. Hurts will need to overcome a shaky and/or unproven group of targets, but he has a very good line and his elite rushing provides a high weekly floor. Consider the 23-year-old a borderline QB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Used heavily in the slot by former coordinator Chan Gailey, it remains to be seen how Gesicki will ultimately fit into Miami's scheme this year. That said, we're still expecting him to be the leading scorer at his position for the Dolphins. That leaves him as a fringe TE1 against the Patriots this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Gesicki is technically a tight end, but really he's a wide receiver. Last season, he aligned in the slot on 70% of his routes, out wide on 19% and was in line only 11% of the time for the Dolphins. The fantasy-friendly role allowed him a career-best 53-703-6 receiving line and seventh-place finish in fantasy points. However, a deeper look suggests he performed more like a TE2 than a TE1, amassing only four top-10 weeks, while finishing outside the top-20 five times. But there are plusses. He's handled exactly 11 end zone targets and has ranked top-four in aDOT each of the past two seasons. The 25-year-old has more competition for targets in the form of Will Fuller V and Jaylen Waddle this season, but his role is enough to allow fringe TE1 production, especially in non-PPR.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tight ends can be a quarterback's best friend. That's especially true for rookie signal-callers like Mac Jones. Smith projects as a low-end TE1 for New England's Week 1 matchup against the Dolphins.

player.seasonOutlook: Smith signed a four-year, $50 million contract with New England after spending his first four seasons in Tennessee. Smith's 65 targets, 41 receptions and 448 yards last season were career highs, though none ranked better than 17th at the position. He scored nine TDs, but was a bit lucky (6.6 OTD) and totaled eight (4.7 OTD) during his first three seasons. Smith's game is post-catch production, as he's ranked no lower than seventh at TE in RAC each of the past three seasons. He has never finished a season as a top-15 TE and may have trouble hitting that mark with Hunter Henry also on New England's roster (since 2009, only two sets of teammates posted a top-10 fantasy TE campaign in the same season). That said, Mac Jones' promotion to starter certainly helps the team's passing game. The 26-year-old is best-valued as a fringe TE1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Dillon begins the 2021 season as the primary backup for Aaron Jones, most likely to usurp some of the short yardage and red zone responsibility. The big back out of Boston College is athletic enough to be more than just a short-yardage threat, but unless Jones is injured, Dillon is only useful as insurance for those rostering Jones.

player.seasonOutlook: Dillon spent most of his rookie season buried behind Aaron Jones and Jamaal Williams (as expected), which limited him to 263 yards and a pair of TDs on 48 touches. Jones re-signed this offseason, which is bad news for Dillon's upside, but the departure of Williams opens the door for the 2020 second-round pick to play a much larger role. At 6-foot, 247 pounds, the Boston College product is one of the league's biggest backs and he's also extremely athletic for his size (4.53 40-yard dash). The big concern with Dillon is his passing-game limitations (21 receptions in 35 games at BC), but perhaps he can offset some of that with big plays and high-value goal line carries. Dillon is a good bench hold and would leap into the RB2 mix (at least) if Jones were to miss time.

outlooksByWeek.1: Projected to finish just outside of the double-digit fantasy point range, Hardman's secondary role in a high-powered Kansas offense could easily propel him well higher than that in any given week. View him as a risky fringe play against the Browns in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Hardman is an occasional contributor in one of the league's best and highest-volume pass offenses, but the 2019 second-round pick simply has not seen enough volume to warrant fantasy consideration. Hardman has flashed playmaking ability (his 8.7 RAC ranks second among WRs since he was drafted) but didn't see the field much as a rookie (41 targets on 429 snaps) and barely saw an increase in 2020 (62 targets on 475 snaps). The 24-year-old appears to finally be locked into a starting gig opposite Tyreek Hill in 2021, but Demarcus Robinson and Byron Pringle are also in the fold. Hardman is a terrific lottery ticket for your bench.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Washington D/ST finished 2020 as the No. 4 overall fantasy defense. Although they were often up to the task last season, they have a tough Week 1 matchup against Justin Herbert, Austin Ekeler and a pretty strong Chargers offense. Will that offense be clicking on all cylinders out of the gate? Your answer to that question will tell you whether or not to start this D/ST in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: It's been a long time since Washington's D/ST was fantasy-relevant, but the unit posted its first top-15 campaign in more than a decade with a fourth-place finish in 2020. Washington finished no lower than sixth in INTs, sacks, yardage allowed and points allowed. The anchor of the unit is a defensive line that includes four first-round picks (Chase Young, Montez Sweat, Jonathan Allen, Daron Payne), but the secondary added some juice during the offseason with star CB William Jackson joining Kendall Fuller and Landon Collins and the team spent its first-round pick on LB Jamin Davis. Washington's defense returns nine of its top 10 players in snaps from 2020 and is one of the league's best on paper. This is a starting-caliber fantasy D/ST.

outlooksByWeek.1: Marshall is set to start his rookie campaign as Carolina's WR3, working in the slot role previously held down by Curtis Samuel. Projected for single-digit fantasy production in his Week 1 debut against the Jets, there's no need to rush him into your fantasy lineups.

player.seasonOutlook: Marshall was selected by Carolina with the 59th overall pick of April's draft. The LSU star is tall (6-foot-3, 205 pounds) and young (21 years old) with good speed and a large catch radius. He is terrific in contested situations and a threat with the ball in his hands. Mitchell has experience inside and out, having aligned in the slot 83% of the time in 2020. That's notable as Robby Anderson and DJ Moore primarily worked on the perimeter last season with Samuel in the slot. Expect Marshall to step right in as the No. 3 WR in an offense that supported three top-25 fantasy WRs in 2020. If Sam Darnold plays solid ball, Marshall could sneak into fantasy relevance. Grab him with a late pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: Mack does not figure to see much work, be it on the ground or through the air, with Jonathan Taylor and Nyheim Hines each having clearly established roles in both capacities. Mack should not be in your starting lineups this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Mack somewhat surprisingly re-signed with the Colts during the offseason after a lost 2020 campaign in which he went down with a torn ACL in Week 1. The 2017 fourth-round pick ranked top-10 in carries, rushing yards and rushing TDs in 2019, but he's now well behind second-year Jonathan Taylor on a depth chart that also includes passing-game specialist Nyheim Hines.
