Even if Taylor were to miss time, consider that despite reaching 900 rushing yards and eight TDs in each of this past two seasons, Mack has never posted a top-20 fantasy campaign. Injuries (he's missed at least two games in each of his four NFL seasons) and a minimal workload as a receiver (81 career targets) have proven problematic. The 25-year-old does not need to be drafted.

outlooksByWeek.1: As Saquon Barkley’s chief backup, Booker could see more action early in the campaign while Barkley gets back up to speed. That said, Booker is only a roster option for those desiring Barkley insurance.

player.seasonOutlook: Booker signed with the Giants after spending his first four seasons in Denver and 2020 in Las Vegas. Booker hasn't played more than 30% of the snaps in a season since 2016, though he was serviceable off the bench behind Josh Jacobs in 2020. Booker averaged 4.55 YPC (1.84 YAC) on 93 carries and added 84 yards on 21 targets (4.0 YPT). The 29-year-old is a replacement-level player, but is positioned as Saquon Barkley's clear backup in New York. Booker has no standalone value but could handle 15 or so touches per game if Barkley misses time. Consider him as a Barkley insurance policy in deep leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: All indications are Barkley will be able to suit up for the Giants opener against the Broncos in the Meadowlands. He spent the offseason rehabbing after requiring surgery on his ACL and MCL after last season’s Week 2 injury. However, temper expectations to RB2 status until Barkley demonstrates he’s able to handle his usual high workload.

player.seasonOutlook: Barkley returns to the New York backfield in search of a bounceback campaign following a 2020 season in which a knee injury limited him to 64 snaps. Barkley was the feature back, as expected, out of the gate, handling 15 carries and nine targets while playing 88% of the snaps in Week 1. That aligned with his usage during his first two NFL seasons. Barkley paced all RBs in yardage and fantasy points as a rookie in 2018 and ranked third in yardage and fourth in fantasy points during his 12 full games in 2019. There are suddenly a lot of mouths to feed in New York, but, assuming full health, Barkley is one of the few backs in the league who will push for 25 touches every week. The 24-year-old remains an elite RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Heading into Kansas City's Week 1 matchup against the Browns -- a team that actually played solid defense last year -- Edwards-Helaire carries a solid RB2 projection. You know how early you drafted him. You should play him with that value in mind.

player.seasonOutlook: Expectations were sky high for Edwards-Helaire last season after the LSU product was selected by the Super Bowl champion Chiefs in the first round of the draft. Despite being handed a feature role out of the gate, "CEH" didn't live up to expectations, managing only two top-10 fantasy weeks in 13 appearances. Edwards-Helaire's efficiency was pedestrian across the board and he dealt with some bad TD luck (five TDs, 7.8 OTD). On the plus side, the 22-year-old remains in a great spot as the high-scoring Chiefs' lead back and, unlike last year, he won't cost you a first-round pick. Consider him a RB2 option and post-hype sleeper for RB1 numbers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Waller is the rare tight end also serving as his team’s primary receiver. With the wideouts being a combination of developing youngsters and veterans brought in this season, expect Derek Carr to lean on Waller even more, especially early. Week 1 brings the stout Raven defense, but Waller is matchup proof, ranking as one of the top options at the position.

player.seasonOutlook: Waller burst onto the fantasy scene with an impressive third-place showing in 2019. Instead of returning to earth in 2020, he added 60 points to his total. His 11 top-10 fantasy weeks trailed only Travis Kelce (14) and were three more than the next-closest TE. Waller improved in every key fantasy category, but the biggest boost was in the TD department. After scoring three times in 2019 (3.7 OTD), he jumped to nine last season (7.8 OTD). Waller has finished no lower than fifth at TE in snaps, routes, targets, receptions and yardage each of the past two seasons. He'll be in the same system (Jon Gruden) with the same QB (Derek Carr) and with another unproven WR room. The 28-year-old is a top-three fantasy TE.

outlooksByWeek.1: Williams has the size and skills to be a lead back but initially he’ll share backfield duties with Melvin Gordon III. However, with the Broncos likely to play it close to the vest with newcomer Teddy Bridgewater calling signals, Williams could garner ample touches to fill the flex spot in deeper leagues, especially since game flow with the opposing New York Giants will likely entail a ball control approach on both sides.

player.seasonOutlook: Williams was selected by Denver with the 35th pick of the 2021 draft. The North Carolina product's calling card is elite tackle breaking and elusiveness. Williams has the second-best YAC (4.1) and forced missed tackle rates (3.0) in this year's class over the past three seasons and was top-two in both categories in 2020. Williams has good size (5-foot-10, 212 pounds) and is an aggressive and explosive rusher with respectable receiving production (his 25 catches in 2020 were third-most in this class). Williams is one of the youngest backs in this class (21) but will immediately step into a consistent role next to starter Melvin Gordon. He may start slow, but Williams figures to progressively take on more work as the season progresses. He'll be worth of a mid-round pick in season-long leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: While he led the league with 13 drops last season, Johnson is still a rising receiving talent who claimed a massive target share last season. With the trust of his quarterback, Johnson has a real shot at overcoming some challenging matchups in the Buffalo secondary.

player.seasonOutlook: It's not inaccurate to say Johnson "broke out" during his sophomore campaign in 2020, but it was certainly a bizarre showing by the 2019 third-round pick. On the plus side, Johnson did an excellent job getting open, and his 144 targets ranked seventh at the position. In 12 regular-season games he played in full, Johnson averaged a massive 11.2 targets per game and was the No. 4-scoring fantasy WR. On the other hand, Johnson left three games injured, led the NFL with 12 drops and his overall efficiency was atrocious (his 61% catch rate ranked 65th and his 6.4 YPT 82nd among 87 qualified WRs). The 24-year-old is Ben Roethlisberger's top target in Pittsburgh's pass-first offense, so the heavy volume will keep him in the WR2 mix. If his efficiency improves, Johnson could vault even higher.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jeudy’s rookie campaign was a mixed bag as he displayed game-breaking ability but was also second in the league with 13 drops. The Broncos will likely play conservatively at the beginning of the season, so even though Jeudy has top-20 potential, he’s best considered as a WR3 as the Broncos travel to East Rutherford to open the season against an improving New York Giants defensive unit.

player.seasonOutlook: Jeudy was very busy as a rookie, appearing in all 16 of Denver's games while ranking 21st among WRs with 112 targets. The 2020 first-round pick's efficiency did not match his volume, as he dropped eight passes (second most) and his 46% catch rate ranked 86th out of 87 qualified WRs. Jeudy was utilized as a vertical threat (his 14.5 aDOT ranked eighth), but 25% of balls thrown his way were off target (eighth highest). He ended up as WR45 in fantasy with only two top-30 fantasy weeks. The talented 22-year-old will be a candidate for a second-year leap, but more volume isn't a lock with Courtland Sutton back and KJ Hamler, Tim Patrick and Noah Fant also involved in Denver's run-heavy scheme led by an unproven Drew Lock. Jeudy will be a risky mid-round pick, but he has upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: The sample size working with Jalen Hurts at Alabama wasn't very big, but Smith did post 207 yards on just 12 catches a few years back. Maybe Smith can pick up where he left off in a matchup with a Falcons defense that allowed the most fantasy points to receivers last season.

player.seasonOutlook: The Eagles traded up to select Smith with the 10th overall pick of April's draft. The reigning Heisman Trophy winner, Smith put up 1,856 yards and 23 TDs during his dominant 2020 campaign. The big knock on the Alabama star is size (6-foot-1, 175 pounds), but his ball skills are unmatched in this class and he has the versatility, speed, quickness, separation ability, route-running prowess and hands (six drops on 298 targets over the past three seasons) to emerge as a high-volume, elite NFL wide receiver. Smith joins Jalen Reagor as the Eagles clear-cut top two WRs and, while it's yet to be seen if Jalen Hurts will develop into a capable NFL starter, we at least know Smith will be a full-timer out of the gate. He's a flex option with obvious upside for more.

outlooksByWeek.1: Davis opens the season as New York's de facto WR1 after a strong summer in which he demonstrated a solid connection with rookie QB Zach Wilson. It's a combination that could surprise at some point this season. For now, however, Davis is best viewed as a fringe WR3 against the Panthers in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Davis signed with the Jets after four seasons with the Titans. The 2017 fifth-overall pick underwhelmed during his first three seasons, despite heavy usage, but progressed a bit in 2020 with a 65-984-5 receiving line on 94 targets. It was easily his most efficient season, as he caught 71% of his targets despite a career-high 12.2 aDOT. That helped him to 10.7 YPT (seventh best at WR) and 2.7 YPRR (fourth). Davis is ticketed for an every-down role in New York, but he has yet to post a single top-25 fantasy campaign and will now be working in a potentially run-first and low-scoring scheme with a rookie QB and a crowded WR room (Jamison Crowder, Elijah Moore, Keelan Cole, Denzel Mims). The 26-year-old is a WR3/flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: Miami drafted Waddle at No. 6 overall to be a playmaking piece in this offense. The question is how long it takes the rookie to show that kind of ability at the professional level. Our Week 1 projection suggests that it won't be against the Patriots.

player.seasonOutlook: Waddle was selected by Miami with the sixth-overall pick of April's draft. The Alabama star is arguably the most explosive WR this year's class, as he sports elite speed, athleticism and playmaking ability. He's on the small side (5-foot-10, 182 pounds) and totaled only 131 targets in three seasons with the Crimson Tide, but his 15.3 YPT, 3.7 YPRR, 10.0 RAC and 81% catch rate during that span are all best in this year's rookie class. Waddle has the ability to play inside or out (he aligned in the slot 71% of the time at Alabama) and figures to begin his career inside with Will Fuller V and DeVante Parker on the perimeter. Waddle might be limited for targets a bit early on, but his talent and pedigree makes him worth a mid-round pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: Stafford did not play a single down for his new club in the preseason. Don’t worry, it was by design, he’s fully healthy entering Week 1’s home matchup with the solid Chicago Bears defense. There will be weeks Stafford is a clear QB1, but he opens the season just outside the tier in his Rams debut.

player.seasonOutlook: Stafford was traded to the Rams during the offseason following 12 seasons in Detroit. The 33-year-old is eyeing a bounce-back campaign; Although Stafford finished as a top-nine fantasy QB six times in the past decade, he hasn't done so since 2017. Stafford's fantasy upside is certainty limited by a lack of rushing contributions (347 rush yards and 0 TDs over the past four years), but his passing production and efficiency is likely to improve under Sean McVay and with a Robert Woods and Cooper Kupp at his disposal. Note that Stafford has ranked top-3 in average depth of throw in each of the past two seasons. Consider Stafford a good QB2 option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Both fantasy managers and 49ers fan will need to be patient with Lance this season, as it appears the team is going to integrate him into the offense as the season evolves. You can't use Lance yet in lineups, but there's a real shot he sees the field in a meeting with a weak Detroit defense.

player.seasonOutlook: Lance was selected by the 49ers with the third overall pick of April's draft. The North Dakota State product has a solid frame at 6-foot-4, 224 pounds and his best assets are his huge arm and rushing ability. N.D. State didn't play in 2020 due to COVID, but Lance threw for 2,789 yards (9.7 YPA) and ran for 1,110 (6.5 YPC) in 16 games in 2019. Lance's shaky accuracy and a severe lack of experience (one full season as starter, 17.9 pass attempts per game) are concern areas, but his combination of size, arm talent and rushing ability supplies plenty of upside. Lance may not start early on, but it's only a matter of time until he overtakes Jimmy Garoppolo. With a good supporting cast and Kyle Shanahan running the show, Lance will have some fantasy appeal, so he's worth late-round consideration.

outlooksByWeek.1: Filling a crucial role as the third-down playmaking threat for Tom Brady this season, Bernard likely claims the most intriguing fantasy profile out of this backfield in PPR formats. Healing from a preseason injury and limited to a specialized role, you shouldn't trust Bernard in lineups against a reworked Dallas defense.

player.seasonOutlook: Bernard signed with Buccaneers after eight seasons with the Bengals. Bernard ranked 26th among RBs with 171 touches last season and, while that may not seem like much, he totaled 174 during the 2018-19 seasons. Bernard's production was all over the map, however, as he reached 20 fantasy points in four games after Joe Mixon's Week 6 season-ending injury, but was in single digits the other six weeks. Bernard is still a capable receiver (81% catch rate, 6.1 YPT in 2020), but has struggled badly as a rusher recently (his 3.4 YPC is fourth worst and his 1.5 YAC eighth worst among 57 RBs with 200-plus carries since 2018). The 29-year-old will see the passing down work, but Leonard Fournette and Ronald Jones II will handle most of the carries in Tampa Bay. Bernard is worth a late pick in PPR.

outlooksByWeek.1: Davis paced the Bills with an average depth of target of 15.2 yards last season, a rate that ranks ninth-deepest in the league and third-highest among players with at least 60 targets. This field-stretching role comes with a low fantasy floor in a matchup with a top pass defense.

player.seasonOutlook: Davis was very busy as a fourth-round rookie last season, playing 754 snaps, which ranked fifth among rookie WRs and 34th overall at the position. The UCF product benefited from John Brown's injuries, as well as a Bills offense that was second pass-heaviest in the NFL and ranked first in three-plus WR sets (94%) and second in four-plus WR sets (17%) when passing. Brown is gone and Emmanuel Sanders is in behind Stefon Diggs and Cole Beasley, but keep in mind that Davis played 68% of the snaps and handled 19% of the team's air yards as a 21-year-old rookie. Davis ranked top-5 in YPR (17.1) and aDOT (15.1), and his role in Buffalo's Josh Allen-led offense may increase in 2021. He's a fine late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: Until Daniel Jones proves otherwise, playing the D/ST facing the New York Giants is a top play. If the Broncos D/ST is available, strongly consider using them as your Week 1 D/ST.

player.seasonOutlook: Vic Fangio is one of the league's top defensive minds, but it has yet to translate to Denver's D/ST, as the unit has posted finishes of 19th and 22nd over the past two seasons. The Broncos finished outside the top 20 in INTs and forced fumbles both seasons, but even without Von Miller, leaped to ninth in sacks (42) in 2020. Expect things to improve in 2021. Miller will return after missing all of 2020, Kyle Fuller, Ronald Darby and first-round pick Patrick Surtain II were added to a very strong secondary and Denver's top 10 players in 2020 snaps remain on the roster. The talent is solid across the board thanks to the likes of Justin Simmons, Kareem Jackson, Bryce Callahan, Bradley Chubb, Dre'Mont Jones and Shelby Harris, so we should expect Denver to, at least, leap into the top 10 at D/ST this season.

outlooksByWeek.1: A gifted receiver while at Memphis, Gainwell is a real threat to assume the satellite back role in this offense. Atlanta was respectable defending backfields last season, with Gainwell still just a deep-league stash.

player.seasonOutlook: Gainwell was selected by Eagles in the fifth round of April's draft. The Memphis product is 5-foot-11, 201 pounds and an undersized scat back with average speed who figures to make his name as a pass catcher and perhaps in the slot WR in the pros. Gainwell's receiving prowess is apparent, as he averaged a massive 9.7 YPT during his final two FBS seasons. Gainwell opted out of the 2020 season, so we haven't seen him in a while, and, though he did handle a big workload in 2019, his size and skillset is unlikely to allow him much goal line work or a three-down role in the pros. He'll open his career battling Boston Scott for change-of-pace/passing-down role behind feature back Miles Sanders. Draft the rookie in only very deep PPR leagues.

Bass was fantasy's No. 4 kicker as a rookie in 2020. The sixth-round pick's career started slowly, as he managed seven or fewer points in his first six games, but he finished strong with a position-best 116 fantasy points after Week 6. He benefited from the Bills' high-scoring offense, as his 59 extra-point attempts were second most and his 34 field goal attempts seventh most among kickers. Bass' field goal accuracy was slightly below average (82.4%), but the 24-year-old will surely be busy again in the same situation in 2021. He's a back-end starting kicker option in most formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: As a primary piece of the Kansas City offense, no player in the NFL offers more leverage at their position than Kelce does at tight end. Our projections for his Week 1 matchup against the Browns have him nearly four points ahead of the field, reflecting his greatness.

player.seasonOutlook: The last time Kelce did not finish as a season as the top-scoring fantasy TE, Patrick Mahomes was still a year away from declaring for the NFL draft. Kelce has paced the field in five consecutive seasons, ranking no lower than fourth at the position in routes, targets, receptions and yardage each year. As if he wasn't already dominating enough, Kelce set career high marks in catches (105), receiving yards (NFL-record 1,416), TDs (11) and fantasy points (313) in 2020. He posted a top-five fantasy week in 13 of 15 appearances, finishing lower than ninth just once. In addition to benefiting from Mahomes and pass-heavy Andy Reid, the 31-year-old is so good that he's worth considering in the first round.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season marked the first in Mixon's career with fewer than 14 games played, so it likely flew under the radar that he was on pace for 1,500 yards and a career-high 56 catches before getting injured. The Vikings have retooled their defense, but this could be a fun matchup for Mixon given that Minnesota allowed the sixth-most rushing yards last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Mixon is entering his fifth NFL season after an injury-plagued 2020 campaign in which he was limited to six games. Mixon was busy those weeks, handling 81% of Cincinnati's carries and 12% of the targets while sitting 10th among RBs in fantasy points per game. For perspective, he handled 75% of the carries and 8% of the targets in 16 games while finishing as RB13 in 2019. Mixon is only 24 years old and has now delivered solid RB2 numbers in three-consecutive seasons. An early-down feature back with a rising target share (especially with Giovani Bernard gone) and a healthy Joe Burrow under center, Mixon's outlook is on the upswing. He's a good RB2 target with RB1 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jacobs returns as the Raiders lead back, though his fantasy production is likely to take a hit with Kenyan Drake joining him as the No. 2 running back. Jacobs should still get ample handles to be a borderline RB1 at times, though it’s best to expect RB2 production as Las Vegas entertains the stingy Ravens defense in the 2021 debut of Monday Night Football.

player.seasonOutlook: Jacobs returns as the lead back in Las Vegas, but he'll have more competition for touches this season after the team signed Kenyan Drake. Jacobs finished eighth at RB in fantasy points 2020, ranking no lower than seventh in carries (273), rushing yards (1,065), TDs (12), and carries inside the 5-yard line (18). However, his efficiency plummeted across the board relative to an impressive rookie campaign. The 2019 first-round pick's heavy role as a rusher and near the goal line won't disappear, but he's simply not much of a factor as a receiver (career 5.5 YPT on 73 targets) and, even before Drake arrived, he showed a low ceiling, posting only three top-10 fantasy weeks (18 RBs had more) in 2020. The 23-year-old is an uninspiring mid-to-back-end RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Even in a year that saw Godwin struggle with multiple injuries, the Penn State product delivered another strong fantasy season. Now healthy and playing for a big deal, Godwin is a surefire WR2 option with room for more against the Dallas secondary.

player.seasonOutlook: Godwin missed four regular-season games in 2020, but if we include the playoffs, he appeared in 16 games and posted a healthy 81-1,072-8 receiving line on 116 targets. That would've been good enough for a WR15 finish during the regular season and was a step down from his 86-1,333-9 line on 120 targets in 14 games in 2019. In 10 "full" games with Mike Evans and Antonio Brown, Godwin saw 71 targets (19% share), but was limited to 125 fantasy points (12.5 PPG extrapolated over 16 games would've ranked 28th last season). Godwin is one of the league's best WRs (he's finished top-10 in catch rate and YPT each of the past two seasons), but his target ceiling is a bit limited with Evans and Brown back in the Buccaneers' spread-it-around attack. Consider the 25-year-old a back-end WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Even expecting a run-heavy approach with rookie Mac Jones at quarterback, it behooves you to keep expectations for Harris within reason.  Epxect no more than low-end RB2/flex level production for Week 1 against Miami.

player.seasonOutlook: We finally got a long look at Harris last season after the 2019 third-round pick was limited to five snaps as a rookie. Harris made his 2020 debut in Week 4 and went on to rack up 743 yards and a pair of TDs on 142 touches. He impressed as a rusher (5.0 YPC, 2.0 YAC) despite facing 7.4 box defenders per carry (second highest), but was uninvolved as a receiver (eight targets). Harris was RB24 in fantasy during 10 active weeks, managing one weekly finish better than 19th (11th). The 24-year-old will share carries with the likes of rookie Rhamondre Stevenson and J.J. Taylor, and James White is back as the team's primary receiving back. Harris is on the flex radar, especially in non-PPR leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Although Wilson passed over 4,000 yards in 2020, it's possible that Pete Carroll wants to return to a more run-heavy approach in 2021. Seattle's new Offensive Coordinator Shane Waldron has talked about running a faster-paced offense, with a more diverse route tree. Regardless of the opponent, trust Wilson as a QB1 until we see proof that the Seahawks are going to seek out a completely different style of play.

player.seasonOutlook: Wilson is back as the starter in Seattle, which was not always a given during what was a bit of a rocky offseason. The drama comes after a bizarre 2020 campaign in which Wilson opened the season with six top-7 fantasy weeks in eight games before managing zero after Week 8. Wilson's hot start was enough for his ninth-consecutive top-11 fantasy campaign (he's also finished top-3 in pass TDs each of the past four seasons), but Pete Carroll's penchant for a run-first offense figures to cap Wilson's pass volume moving forward. Wilson is now 32 years old, but still adds value with his legs (fourth among QBs in rushing yards in 2020). Consider him a mid-range QB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: In 2020, Anderson posted the first 1,000-yard season of his NFL career and quietly finished as a top-20 fantasy option. Now reunited with former Jets teammate Sam Darnold, Anderson is poised to take another step forward in 2021. View him as a solid WR2 this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Anderson is entering his second season with the Panthers after a successful 2020 campaign in which he handled a career-high 8.5 targets per game (26% share) and finished as fantasy's No. 19-scoring WR. Anderson's role was much different than it was with the Jets, as he was used less as a vertical weapon (9.4 aDOT compared to 14.8 with Jets), which led to career-high showings in targets, receptions and receiving yards. The only problem area for Anderson was scoring TDs, as he found pay dirt only three times (his fewest since 2016). The 28-year-old is ticketed for a similar role in 2021 and very well could benefit from Sam Darnold's arrival, Curtis Samuel's departure and some regression to the mean in the TD department. Anderson is a fine WR3 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Serving as a field-stretcher last season without much variety in his route tree, Gallup struggled to build on his strong 2019 effort. Training camp buzz suggests Gallup could benefit from more work out of the slot, but it's difficult to trust him in lineups just yet for this meeting with the Bucs.

player.seasonOutlook: Back in 2019, Gallup broke out with a 66-1,107-6 receiving line and a WR22 fantasy campaign in 14 games. In the offseason that followed, Dallas changed coaching staffs and drafted CeeDee Lamb in the first round. As expected, Gallup's usage and production took a hit. Despite finishing second among all WRs in routes (601), Gallup was limited to a 59-843-5 line and a WR38 fantasy showing (including three weekly finishes better than 34th). Dak Prescott's Week 5 season-ending injury is notable, but Gallup was averaging 5.4 targets per game and was WR33 in fantasy for Prescott's starts. He averaged 7.2 per game and was WR38 in his final 11 weeks of action. The 25-year-old is a good player in a great and high-volume, though crowded, offense. Prescott's third priority is best-valued as a flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: Raiders head coach Jon Gruden favors tandem running backs so Drake was brought in as the change-of-pace partner to Josh Jacobs more bruising style. Jacobs still has the edge in terms of touches, though Drake should see the field sufficiently to be a deep league flex option, especially in Week 1 as Las Vegas will likely feature the ground game in their opener against the solid Ravens defenders.

player.seasonOutlook: Drake's value went the wrong direction during the offseason, as he's headed from feature back duties in Arizona to a complementary role behind Josh Jacobs in Las Vegas. Last season, Drake finished no lower than 12th among RBs in snaps (594), carries (239), rushing yards (955) and TDs (10), while ranking second in the NFL in carries inside the 5 (21) and third in OTD (13.4). He won't come close to that usage with the Raiders. Drake was limited to 31 targets in 2020 but totaled 139 the prior two seasons in Miami and Arizona. Though his receiving efficiency hasn't been good (career 5.5 YPT on 226 targets), Drake figures to return to a more prominent role in that department, with Jacobs handling most of the carries and goal-line work. Drake is a PPR flex and very good insurance policy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ruggs is coming off an unspectacular rookie campaign, though the Raiders expect big things from the 11th overall pick in the 2020 draft. To that end, Ruggs added muscle to his frame in the offseason but he still is someone to monitor, but not yet trust, for fantasy purposes, especially since the Raiders kick off the season at home against the talented Ravens secondary.

player.seasonOutlook: Ruggs was the first wide receiver selected from the loaded 2020 draft class, but the pedigree did not translate to the field during his rookie campaign. Ruggs appeared in 13 games and played a healthy 555 snaps, but he was held to a 26-452-2 receiving line on 43 targets, adding 49 yards on nine carries. He posted two weekly fantasy finishes better than 46th. Ruggs has world class speed at 4.27 and was utilized as a vertical threat as a rookie (16.9 aDOT), but 3.3 targets per game (no more than five in a single game) simply won't cut it. Las Vegas' shaky WR depth chart gives Ruggs a real shot to emerge as the team's No. 1 WR, so a breakout is likely -- if he can translate his skill set to the pros. Grab him for your bench.

outlooksByWeek.1: The league's top rush defense for the past two seasons, Tampa Bay is in a good position to force Dallas to be one-dimensional. One holdup is just how prolific the Dallas passing game could prove to be.

player.seasonOutlook: The Buccaneers will enter 2021 with their entire starting lineup from last season's Super Bowl champion squad. In fact, all 19 players who played at least 59 defensive snaps for Tampa Bay last season remain on the roster. The 2020 unit ranked no lower than eighth in INTs, forced fumbles, sacks, yardage allowed or points allowed. The Bucs have a good secondary led by Carlton Davis and terrific duos at DT (Vita Vea, Ndamukong Suh), edge (Shaquil Barrett, Jason Pierre-Paul) and LB (Lavonte David, Devin White). Tampa Bay's D/ST is fresh off back-to-back top-10 fantasy campaigns and is well positioned for a leap to the elite in 2021.

outlooksByWeek.1: A quiet rookie season mired by injuries and underwhelming play could give way to a more promising second campaign for Reagor. A big-play threat in college, Reagor will get his chance to shine against a suspect Atlanta secondary.

player.seasonOutlook: The 2020 season was a rough one for the Eagles' offense, and that was highlighted by injuries and poor QB play. Both affected Reagor, as the rookie was limited to 11 games and 26% of balls thrown his direction were off target (fourth highest among WRs). The 2020 first-round pick ended up with a 31-396-1 receiving line and zero top-30 fantasy weeks. On the plus side, the scheme and QB will be different (albeit unproven) this season, and Reagor, whose 5.7 RAC ranked 11th among WRs, is likely to play an every-down role opposite rookie De'Vonta Smith. Reagor will see consistent targets in an offense lacking weapons and that will likely be throwing often in the second half of games. The 22-year-old is a logical post-hype breakout candidate and good mid-round target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Like the team's new coaching staff, Coleman previously worked for the 49ers. His familiarity with the scheme and a dearth of proven talent at the position in New York leave him as the likely early-down option to open the season. That doesn't, however, make Coleman a viable fantasy option against Carolina in Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Coleman signed with the Jets and will compete for work with fourth-round rookie Michael Carter. Following a promising start to his career during four seasons in Atlanta, Coleman missed 10 games and didn't live up to expectations during the past two seasons in San Francisco. The 2015 third-round pick was a top-22 fantasy RB in three consecutive seasons spanning 2016-18, but fell to 39th in 2019 and was reduced to only 87 yards on 32 touches in eight games in 2020. The 28-year-old is best-served for situational duties and will only join the flex radar if injuries force him into a starting role. He's worth a late flier simply due to his situation.

outlooksByWeek.1: Is he an insurance policy for Miles Gaskins? Is he a threat to steal goal-line carries from him? Both are possible for Brown, who makes his Dolphins debut against the Patriots in Week 1. Fantasy managers should limit exposure to him until we get a feel for exactly how Miami plans to use him.

player.seasonOutlook: Brown signed with the Dolphins after spending the first six seasons of his career with the Rams. The 2015 UDFA easily set career-high marks in carries (110), rushing yardage (449), targets (35), receptions (25) and receiving yards (175) last season, but a lot of that damage was done during his only two top-20 fantasy weeks. Brown has scored five TDs each of the past two seasons, but has yet to finish a season as a top-40 fantasy RB. The 28-year-old will be a part of the committee in Miami, but Myles Gaskin will be the main back with Salvon Ahmed also involved. Brown is only worth a late pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: Likely to lose some snaps and targets to Pat Freiermuth as the season matures, Ebron is at least on the streaming radar at this shallow position thanks to an inviting matchup with a Buffalo defense that allowed the fifth-most fantasy points to tight ends last year.

player.seasonOutlook: Ebron's 2020 season - his first with Pittsburgh - started slowly, but he quietly finished 10th or better at the position in routes, targets, receptions and OTD, while landing 12th in fantasy points per game. Ebron posted three games with 11-plus targets after Week 11 and was fantasy's No. 8 TE after Week 2. Ebron played 73% of the snaps when active last season and his primary competition for work is rookie Pat Freiermuth in a Steelers' offense that has posted a TE target share of at least 15% each of the past 12 seasons. Ebron is likely to be undervalued in 2021 drafts, as the 28-year-old very much as back-end TE1 upside in the Steelers' pass-heavy scheme.

McManus fell just short of back-to-back top-10 fantasy campaigns last season, but it wasn't for a lack of strong play. McManus was asked to attempt an NFL record 15 field goals of 50-plus yards (he tied an NFL record by making 10). His seemingly weak 82.4 FG% for the season was actually well above his 72.8% expected rate based on distance and was actually the most efficient season of his career (he was 18-of-19 on FG attempts under 50 yards). The 30-year-old is one of the best in the business and benefits from nine games in the thin, mile-high air this season. He's a fine fantasy starter.
